{"title_page": "Egon Hanfstaengl", "text_new": "{{Orphan|date=February 2020}}\n\n{{short description|German art publisher}}\n'''Egon Ludwig Sedgwick Hanfstaengl''' ({{IPA-de|\u025b\u0261\u0254n hanf.\u02c8\u0283t\u025b\u014bl|}} February 3, 1921<ref>Peter Conradi, Hitler's Piano Player, 2006, Seite 34</ref> - March 21, 2007) was a German art publisher and also [[Adolf Hitler|Adolf Hitler's]] godchild. He was the son of [[Ernst Hanfstaengl]].\n{{Infobox person\n|name          = Egon Hanfstaengl\n|image         = Egon_Hanfstaengl_In_A_Interview.jpg\n|caption       = Egon Hanfstaengel in an interview with zeitzeugen-portal\n|birth_name    = Egon Sedgwick Hanfstaengl\n|birth_date    = {{birth date|df=y|1921|2|3}}\n|birth_place   = [[New York City, New York]], U.S.\n|death_date    = {{death date and age|df=y|2007|3|21|1921|2|3}}\n|death_place   = United States\n|nationality   = \n|residence     = \n|known_for     = Being the godchild of [[Adolf Hitler]]\n|education     = \n|alma mater    = \n|occupation    = \n|title         = \n|salary        = \n|networth      = \n|spouse        = \n|children      = \n|signature     = \n|signature_alt = \n|website       = \n}}\n\n== Life ==\n\nEgon Hanfstaengl was born on February 3, 1921 in New York City as the son of Ernst Hanfstaengl and Helene Hanfstaengl, n\u00e9e Niemeyer. Hitler became his godfather. He had a sister, Hertha, who died at the age of 5. He received his school education in England and Germany, where he also joined the [[Hitler Youth|Hitler Youth (HJ)]].\n\nHe went to the United States to study and was also an American citizen from birth on. As the son of a prominent former top official of the [[NSDAP]], about whom the American press reported regularly, Hanfstaengl also came into the focus of the reporting. The [[New York Times]] announced the admission of the 18-year-old to [[Harvard University]].<ref>''Hitler Ex-Aide's Son in Harvard.'' In: ''New York Times'', 23. September 1939.</ref> The newspaper also reported that he volunteered for the [[United States Army Air Corps]] in early 1941.<ref>''Hanfstaengl Jr. In Army; Harvard Man, Son of Ex-Nazi, Enlists in American Forces.'' In: ''New York Times, '' 30. Januar 1941.</ref><ref>[[Carlos Widmann]], [http://www.spiegel.de/spiegel/print/d-10126959.html Play it again, Putzi]. ''Der Spiegel'', 10/1999.</ref> The news about Hanfstaengl's entry into the [[US Army]] also received attention from [[Minister of Propaganda]] [[Joseph Goebbels]], he made a corresponding entry in his diary.<ref>''Die Tageb\u00fccher von Joseph Goebbels.'' Hrsg. Elke Fr\u00f6hlich. T. I, Bd. 9. M\u00fcnchen 1998, S. 119.</ref>\n\nJournalist [[John Franklin Carter]], who, as a consultant to [[US President]] [[Franklin D. Roosevelt]], had psychological assessments prepared of some Nazi leaders, also asked Hanfstaengl's father and his son. When Hanfstaengl started working on a book about the HJ, Roosevelt, who knew his father Ernst Hanfstaengl from studying in Harvard, spontaneously dictated several paragraphs for a foreword, according to the Carters report.<ref>Joseph E. Persico: ''Roosevelt's Secret War. FDR and World War II Espionage.'' New York 2002, S. 232.</ref> According to American records, Hanfstaengl offered Roosevelt to travel to Hitler in the [[Berghof (residence)|Berghof]] near [[Berchtesgaden]] in 1943 to attack him, but the White House ignored this suggestion.<ref>Joseph E. Persico: ''Roosevelt's Secret War. FDR and World War II Espionage.'' New York 2002, S. 332.</ref>\n\nAfter [[World War II]], Hanfstaengl was a lecturer in European and American history at [[Brooklyn College]] in New York. From 1958 until its dissolution in 1980, he was managing director of the art and publishing house Franz Hanfstaengl in [[Munich]]. As the godchild of Adolf Hitler, he appeared in several [[Adolf Hitler in popular culture|documentaries about Hitler]].\n\nHe died on March 21, 2007 at the age of 86.\n\n== Literature ==\n\n* [[Ulrich Chaussy]]: ''Zweimal Amerika und zur\u00fcck nach Bayern: das bewegte Leben des Egon Hanfstaengl.'' Bayerischer Rundfunk, 2000.\n\n== References ==\n\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Hanfstaengl, Egon}}\n[[Category:1921 births]]\n[[Category:2007 deaths]]\n", "text_old": "{{Orphan|date=February 2020}}\n\n{{short description|German art publisher}}\n'''Egon Ludwig Sedgwick Hanfstaengl''' ({{IPA-de|\u025b\u0261\u0254n hanf.\u02c8\u0283t\u025b\u014bl|}} February 3, 1921<ref>Peter Conradi, Hitler's Piano Player, 2006, Seite 34</ref> - March 21, 2007) was a German art publisher and also [[Adolf Hitler|Adolf Hitler's]] godchild. He was the son of [[Ernst Hanfstaengl]].\n{{Infobox person\n|name          = Egon Hanfstaengl\n|image         = Egon_Hanfstaengl_In_A_Interview.jpg\n|caption       = Egon Hanfstaengel in an interview with zeitzeugen-portal\n|birth_name    = Egon Sedgwick Hanfstaengl\n|birth_date    = {{birth date|df=y|1921|2|3}}\n|birth_place   = [[New York City, New York]], U.S.\n|death_date    = {{death date and age|df=y|2007|3|21|1921|2|3}}\n|death_place   = United States\n|nationality   = \n|residence     = \n|known_for     = Being the godchild of [[Adolf Hitler]]\n|education     = \n|alma mater    = \n|occupation    = \n|title         = \n|salary        = \n|networth      = \n|spouse        = \n|children      = \n|signature     = \n|signature_alt = \n|website       = \n}}\n\n== Life ==\n\nEgon Hanfstaengl was born on February 3, 1921 in New York City as the son of Ernst Hanfstaengl and Helene Hanfstaengl, n\u00e9e Niemeyer. Hitler became his godfather. He had a sister, Hertha, who died at the age of 5. He received his school education in England and Germany, where he also joined the [[Hitler Youth|Hitler Youth (HJ)]].\n\nHe went to the United States to study and was also an American citizen from birth on. As the son of a prominent former top official of the [[NSDAP]], about whom the American press reported regularly, Hanfstaengl also came into the focus of the reporting. The [[New York Times]] announced the admission of the 18-year-old to [[Harvard University]].<ref>''Hitler Ex-Aide's Son in Harvard.'' In: ''New York Times'', 23. September 1939.</ref> The newspaper also reported that he volunteered for the [[United States Army Air Corps]] in early [[1941]].<ref>''Hanfstaengl Jr. In Army; Harvard Man, Son of Ex-Nazi, Enlists in American Forces.'' In: ''New York Times, '' 30. Januar 1941.</ref><ref>[[Carlos Widmann]], [http://www.spiegel.de/spiegel/print/d-10126959.html Play it again, Putzi]. ''Der Spiegel'', 10/1999.</ref> The news about Hanfstaengl's entry into the [[US Army]] also received attention from [[Minister of Propaganda]] [[Joseph Goebbels]], he made a corresponding entry in his diary.<ref>''Die Tageb\u00fccher von Joseph Goebbels.'' Hrsg. Elke Fr\u00f6hlich. T. I, Bd. 9. M\u00fcnchen 1998, S. 119.</ref>\n\nJournalist [[John Franklin Carter]], who, as a consultant to [[US President]] [[Franklin D. Roosevelt]], had psychological assessments prepared of some Nazi leaders, also asked Hanfstaengl's father and his son. When Hanfstaengl started working on a book about the HJ, Roosevelt, who knew his father Ernst Hanfstaengl from studying in Harvard, spontaneously dictated several paragraphs for a foreword, according to the Carters report.<ref>Joseph E. Persico: ''Roosevelt's Secret War. FDR and World War II Espionage.'' New York 2002, S. 232.</ref> According to American records, Hanfstaengl offered Roosevelt to travel to Hitler in the [[Berghof (residence)|Berghof]] near [[Berchtesgaden]] in [[1943]] to attack him, but the White House ignored this suggestion.<ref>Joseph E. Persico: ''Roosevelt's Secret War. FDR and World War II Espionage.'' New York 2002, S. 332.</ref>\n\nAfter [[World War II]], Hanfstaengl was a lecturer in European and American history at [[Brooklyn College]] in New York. From [[1958]] until its dissolution in [[1980]], he was managing director of the art and publishing house Franz Hanfstaengl in [[Munich]]. As the godchild of Adolf Hitler, he appeared in several [[Adolf Hitler in popular culture|documentaries about Hitler]].\n\nHe died on March 21 2007 at the age of 86.\n\n== Literature ==\n\n* [[Ulrich Chaussy]]: ''Zweimal Amerika und zur\u00fcck nach Bayern: das bewegte Leben des Egon Hanfstaengl.'' Bayerischer Rundfunk, 2000.\n\n== References ==\n\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Hanfstaengl, Egon}}\n[[Category:1921 births]]\n[[Category:2007 deaths]]\n", "name_user": "GoingBatty", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eLife:General fixes, replaced:1941\u2192 1941 (4)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Egon_Hanfstaengl"}
{"title_page": "Putnam Hill Historic District", "text_new": "{{Infobox NRHP\n  | name = Putnam Hill Historic District\n  |  nrhp_type = hd    |  nocat = yes  \n  | image = Second Congregational Church, Greenwich, Connecticut.jpg\n  | caption = \n  | location= [[United States Route 1|U.S. 1]], [[Greenwich, Connecticut]]\n  | coordinates = {{coord|41|2|11|N|73|37|9|W|display=inline,title}}\n  | locmapin = Connecticut#USA\n  | built = {{start date|1830}}\n  | architect = [[Calvert Vaux|Vaux, Calvert]]; Multiple\n  | architecture = Mid 19th Century Revival, Late 19th and 20th Century Revivals, Late Victorian\n  | added = August 24, 1979\n  | area = {{convert|36|acre|ha}}\n  | governing_body = Local\n  | refnum = 79002657<ref name=\"nris\">{{NRISref|2009a}}</ref>\n}}\nThe '''Putnam Hill Historic District''' encompasses a former town center of [[Greenwich, Connecticut]].  Located on [[United States Route 1]] between Millbank Avenue and Old Church Road, the district includes the churches of two historic congregations, a former tavern, and a collection of fine mid-Victorian residential architecture.  The district was listed on the [[National Register of Historic Places]] in 1979.<ref name=\"nris\"/>\n\n==Description and history==\nGreenwich's Putnam Hill area became a secondary center to the town (after [[Old Greenwich, Connecticut|Old Greenwich]]) at least as early as 1702, when the Second Congregational Church was located there.  It was also home to Greenwich's town hall between 1825 and 1874, which was located where the town's Civil War memorial now stands.  During the [[American Revolutionary War]] it was the scene of an escape of [[Continental Army]] General [[Israel Putnam]] from surrounding British forces by riding his horse down the steep hill from the [[Putnam Cottage]], a feat that gave the area its present name.  The Putnam Cottage, formerly Knapp's Tavern, was built about 1700, and is now a museum.  In the years after the [[American Civil War]], the area developed as a fashionable residential area, with several fine period residences surviving, including the Chateauesque Tomes-Higgins House, which was designed by architect [[Calvert Vaux]].  It was also where [[Boss Tweed]] had his country estate.<ref name=\"nrhpinv3\"/>\n\nThe district is basically linear in extent, running from Millbank Drive in the west to Old Church Road in the east.  The district has 21 [[contributing buildings]], most of which are residential.  Other features of the district are two small parks, a stone marker placed by the DAR commemorating Putnam's ride, the imposing granite wall \"supposedly\" built by Tweed, and the gateway to the former Jeremiah Millbank estate. <ref name=nris/><ref name=\"nrhpinv3\">{{cite web|url={{NRHP url|id=79002657}} |title=National Register of Historic Places Inventory-Nomination: Putnam Hill Historic District / Putnam Hill National Register District |date=October 1978 |author=Charles W. Brilvitch |publisher=National Park Service}} and {{NRHP url|id=79002657|title=''Accompanying 13 photos''|photos=y}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[National Register of Historic Places listings in Greenwich, Connecticut]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Greenwich, Connecticut}}\n{{National Register of Historic Places}}\n\n[[Category:National Register of Historic Places in Fairfield County, Connecticut]]\n[[Category:Georgian architecture in Connecticut]]\n[[Category:Historic districts in Fairfield County, Connecticut]]\n[[Category:Greenwich, Connecticut]]\n[[Category:Historic districts on the National Register of Historic Places in Connecticut]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox NRHP\n  | name = Putnam Hill Historic District\n  |  nrhp_type = hd    |  nocat = yes  \n  | image = Second Congregational Church, Greenwich, Connecticut.jpg\n  | caption = \n  | location= [[United States Route 1|U.S. 1]], [[Greenwich, Connecticut]]\n  | coordinates = {{coord|41|2|11|N|73|37|9|W|display=inline,title}}\n  | locmapin = Connecticut#USA\n  | built = {{start date|1830}}\n  | architect = [[Calvert Vaux|Vaux, Calvert]]; Multiple\n  | architecture = Mid 19th Century Revival, Late 19th and 20th Century Revivals, Late Victorian\n  | added = August 24, 1979\n  | area = {{convert|36|acre|ha}}\n  | governing_body = Local\n  | refnum = 79002657<ref name=\"nris\">{{NRISref|2009a}}</ref>\n}}\nThe '''Putnam Hill Historic District''' encompasses a former town center of [[Greenwich, Connecticut]].  Located on [[United States Route 1]] between Millbank Avenue and Old Church Road, the district includes the churches of two historic congregations, a former tavern, and a collection of fine mid-Victorian residential architecture.  The district was listed on the [[National Register of Historic Places]] in 1979.<ref name=\"nris\"/>\n\n==Description and history==\nGreenwich's Putnam Hill area became a secondary center to the town (after [[Old Greenwich, Connecticut|Old Greenwich]]) at least as early as 1702, when the Second Congregational Church was located there.  It was also home to Greenwich's town hall between 1825 and 1874, which was located where the town's Civil War memorial now stands.  During the [[American Revolutionary War]] it was the scene of an escape of [[Continental Army]] General [[Israel Putnam]] from surrounding British forces by riding his horse down the steep hill from the [[Putnam Cottage]], a feat that gave the area its present name.  The Putnam Cottage, formerly Knapp's Tavern, was built about 1700, and is now a museum.  In the years after the [[American Civil War]], the area developed as a fashionable residential area, with several fine period residences surviving, including the Chateauesque Tomes-Higgins House, which was designed by architect [[Calvert Vaux]].  It was also where [[Boss Tweed]] had his country estate.<ref name=\"nrhpinv3\"/>\n\nThe district is basically linear in extent, running from Millbank Drive in the west to Old Church Road in the east.  The district has 21 [[contributing buildings]], most of which are residential.  Other features of the district are two small parks, a stone marker placed by the DAR commemorating Putnam's ride, and the gateway to the former Jeremiah Millbank estate, which is the only surviving element of the Tweed estate.<ref name=nris/><ref name=\"nrhpinv3\">{{cite web|url={{NRHP url|id=79002657}} |title=National Register of Historic Places Inventory-Nomination: Putnam Hill Historic District / Putnam Hill National Register District |date=October 1978 |author=Charles W. Brilvitch |publisher=National Park Service}} and {{NRHP url|id=79002657|title=''Accompanying 13 photos''|photos=y}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[National Register of Historic Places listings in Greenwich, Connecticut]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Greenwich, Connecticut}}\n{{National Register of Historic Places}}\n\n[[Category:National Register of Historic Places in Fairfield County, Connecticut]]\n[[Category:Georgian architecture in Connecticut]]\n[[Category:Historic districts in Fairfield County, Connecticut]]\n[[Category:Greenwich, Connecticut]]\n[[Category:Historic districts on the National Register of Historic Places in Connecticut]]\n", "name_user": "Jebridge", "label": "safe", "comment": "Corrected the details concerning the wall and the gate of the Milbank estate using the NRHP Inventory and Nomination Form 1979.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Putnam_Hill_Historic_District"}
{"title_page": "Newport Pagnell Town F.C.", "text_new": "{{short description|English association football club}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2015}}\n{{Use British English|date=May 2015}}\n{{Infobox football club\n| clubname   = Newport Pagnell Town\n| image      = Newport Pagnell Town Badge.png\n| caption    = \n| image_size = 160px\n| fullname   = Newport Pagnell Town<br>Football Club\n| nickname   = ''The Swans''\n| founded    = 1963\n| ground     = Willen Road, [[Newport Pagnell]], MK16 0DF\n| capacity   = 2,000 (100 seated)<ref name=NLCD2017>Mike Williams & Tony Williams (2016) ''Non-League Club Directory 2017'', Tony Williams Publications, p537 {{ISBN|978-1869833695}}</ref>\n| chairman   = Steve Handley\n| manager    = Gary Flinn\n| league     = {{English football updater|NewporPT}}\n| season     = {{English football updater|NewporPT2}}\n| position   = {{English football updater|NewporPT3}}\n| pattern_la1 = \n| pattern_b1  = \n| pattern_ra1 = \n| pattern_so1 = \n| leftarm1    = 009900\n| body1       = 009900\n| rightarm1   = 009900\n| shorts1     = \n| socks1      = 009900\n| pattern_la2 = \n| pattern_b2  = \n| pattern_ra2 = \n| leftarm2    = 0000FF\n| body2       = 0000FF\n| rightarm2   = 0000FF\n| shorts2     = \n| socks2      = 0000FF\n| website     = http://www.pitchero.com/clubs/newportpagnelltown\n}}\n\n'''Newport Pagnell Town Football Club''' is a [[association football|football]] club based at [[Newport Pagnell]], [[Buckinghamshire]] in [[England]]. They are currently members of the {{English football updater|NewporPT}} and play at Willen Road.\n\n==History==\nThe club was established as Newport Pagnell Wanderers in 1963 following a meeting between a group of players and Town Clerk Frank Hall.<ref name=H>[https://www.clubwebsite.co.uk/newportpagnelltown/History History] Newport Pagnell Town F.C.</ref> They joined the [[North Bucks & District Football League|North Bucks & District League]] in 1964-65 and won the Division Three Shield in their first season.<ref name=H/> Following back to back championship wins, Division Three (1965-66) and Division Two (1966\u201367) the club were promoted to Division One.<ref name=NB1/> They went on to win the Division One title in each of the next three seasons (1967-68, 1968-69, 1969-70), with the reserve team winning Division Two in 1968\u201369 and 1969\u201370.<ref name=NB1>[http://www.nbdfl.co.uk/sitebuildercontent/sitebuilderfiles/nbdflrecords193334to197273.docx NBDFL Records 1933-34 to 1972-73] North Bucks & District League</ref> In 1971-2 the club moved up to Division One of the [[South Midlands League]],<ref>[http://www.nonleaguematters.co.uk/nlmnet/Addons/SML66.html South Midlands League 1966\u20131983] Non-League Matters</ref> having been renamed Newport Pagnell Town.<ref name=H/>\n\nNewport Pagnell Town were Division One runners-up in 1972\u201373, after which they transferred to Division Two of the [[United Counties League]].<ref name=FCHD>{{fchd|id=NEWPORPT|name=Newport Pagnell Town}}</ref> The club finished second in Division Two in [[1975\u201376 United Counties League|1975\u201376]], earning promotion to Division One. After winning the Division One title in [[1981\u201382 United Counties League|1981\u201382]], they were promoted to the Premier Division. The club finished bottom of the Premier Division in [[1985\u201386 United Counties League|1985\u201386]] and was relegated back to Division One. They were Division One runners-up in [[1991\u201392 United Counties League|1991\u201392]], earning promotion back to the Premier Division, but were relegated to Division One after finishing bottom of the Premier Division in [[1996\u201397 United Counties League|1996\u201397]].<ref name=FCHD/>\n\nIn [[2001\u201302 United Counties League|2001\u201302]] Newport Pagnell were Division One champions and were promoted to the Premier Division, as well as winning the Berks & Bucks FA Intermediate Cup.<ref name=NLCD2017/> They were Premier Division runners-up the [[2002\u201303 United Counties League|following season]].<ref name=FCHD/> The club won the Berks & Bucks FA Senior Trophy in 2009\u201310 and retained it in 2010\u201311.<ref name=NLCD2017/> At the end of the [[2018\u201319 United Counties League|2018\u201319 season]] they were transferred to the Premier Division of the [[Spartan South Midlands Football League|Spartan South Midlands League]].\n\n==Ground==\nWillen Road, Newport Pagnell, Buckinghamshire. MK16 0DF\n\nThe club initially played on a pitch on Bury Field Common, using the Cannon pub on Union Street as changing rooms.<ref name=H/> When they moved up to the South Midlands League in 1971 the club played at the Youth Club in Wolverton Road, before relocating to the Willen Road Sports Ground in 1972.<ref name=H/> The new ground was opened with a match against [[Bletchley Town F.C.|Bletchley Town]].<ref name=H/> Willen Road currently has a capacity of 2,000, of which 100 is seated and covered.<ref name=NLCD2017/>\n\n==Honours==\n*'''United Counties League'''\n**Premier Division - runners up 2002-03\n**Division One - champions 1981\u201382, 2001\u201302 runners up 1991-92\n**Division Two - runners up 1975-76\n**League Knockout Cup - runners up 2009-10\n**Division One Knockout Cup - winners 1977-78\n*'''South Midlands League'''\n**Division One - runners up 1972-73\n*'''North Bucks & District League'''\n**Division One - champions 1967\u201368, 1968\u201369, 1969\u201370\n**Division One Shield - winners 1968-69\n**Division Two - champions 1966\u201367\n**Division Two Shield winners - 1966-67\n**Division Three - champions 1965-66\n**Division Three Shield - winners 1964\u201365 runners up 1965-66\n*'''Berks & Bucks FA Senior Trophy'''\n**Winners 2009\u201310, 2010\u20131\n**Runners up 2007-08, 2008-09, 2015-16\n*'''Berks & Bucks FA Intermediate Cup'''\n**Winners 2001\u201302\n**Runners up 1982-83\n\n==Records==\n*Best [[FA Cup]] performance: Second qualifying round, 2008\u201309<ref name=FCHD/>\n*Best [[FA Vase]] performance: Quarter-finals, 2016\u201317<ref name=FCHD/>\n\n==See also==\n*[[:Category:Newport Pagnell Town F.C. players|Newport Pagnell Town F.C. players]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.pitchero.com/clubs/newportpagnelltown Official website]\n\n{{Spartan South Midlands League}}\n{{coord|52|04|36.80|N|0|43|15.93|W|region:GB_type:landmark|display=title}}\n\n[[Category:Football clubs in England]]\n[[Category:Football clubs in Buckinghamshire]]\n[[Category:Association football clubs established in 1963]]\n[[Category:1963 establishments in England]]\n[[Category:Sport in Milton Keynes]]\n[[Category:North Bucks & District Football League]]\n[[Category:South Midlands League]]\n[[Category:United Counties League]]\n[[Category:Spartan South Midlands Football League]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|English association football club}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2015}}\n{{Use British English|date=May 2015}}\n{{Infobox football club\n| clubname   = Newport Pagnell Town\n| image      = Newport Pagnell Town Badge.png\n| caption    = \n| image_size = 160px\n| fullname   = Newport Pagnell Town<br>Football Club\n| nickname   = ''The Swans''\n| founded    = 1963\n| ground     = Willen Road, [[Newport Pagnell]], MK16 0DF\n| capacity   = 2,000 (100 seated)<ref name=NLCD2017>Mike Williams & Tony Williams (2016) ''Non-League Club Directory 2017'', Tony Williams Publications, p537 {{ISBN|978-1869833695}}</ref>\n| chairman   = Steve Handley\n| manager    = Gary Flinn\n| league     = {{English football updater|NewporPT}}\n| season     = {{English football updater|NewporPT2}}\n| position   = {{English football updater|NewporPT3}}\n| pattern_la1 = \n| pattern_b1  = \n| pattern_ra1 = \n| pattern_so1 = \n| leftarm1    = 009900\n| body1       = 009900\n| rightarm1   = 009900\n| shorts1     = \n| socks1      = 009900\n| pattern_la2 = \n| pattern_b2  = \n| pattern_ra2 = \n| leftarm2    = 0000FF\n| body2       = 0000FF\n| rightarm2   = 0000FF\n| shorts2     = \n| socks2      = 0000FF\n| website     = http://www.pitchero.com/clubs/newportpagnelltown\n}}\n\n'''Newport Pagnell Town Football Club''' is a [[association football|football]] club based at [[Newport Pagnell]], [[Buckinghamshire]] in [[England]]. They are currently members of the {{English football updater|NewporPT}} and play at Willen Road.\n\n==History==\nThe club was established as Newport Pagnell Wanderers in 1963 following a meeting between a group of players and Town Clerk Frank Hall.<ref name=H>[https://www.clubwebsite.co.uk/newportpagnelltown/History History] Newport Pagnell Town F.C.</ref> They joined the [[North Bucks & District Football League|North Bucks & District League]] in 1964 and won the Division Three Shield in their first season in the league.<ref name=H/> In 1966\u201367 the club were Division Two champions, earning promotion to Division One.<ref name=NB1/> They went on to win the Division One title in each of the next three seasons, with the reserve team winning Division Two in 1968\u201369 and 1969\u201370.<ref name=NB1>[http://www.nbdfl.co.uk/sitebuildercontent/sitebuilderfiles/nbdflrecords193334to197273.docx NBDFL Records 1933-34 to 1972-73] North Bucks & District League</ref> In 1971 the club moved up to Division One of the [[South Midlands League]],<ref>[http://www.nonleaguematters.co.uk/nlmnet/Addons/SML66.html South Midlands League 1966\u20131983] Non-League Matters</ref> before being renamed Newport Pagnell Town in 1972.<ref name=H/>\n\nNewport Pagnell were Division One runners-up in 1972\u201373, after which they transferred to Division Two of the [[United Counties League]].<ref name=FCHD>{{fchd|id=NEWPORPT|name=Newport Pagnell Town}}</ref> The club finished second in Division Two in [[1975\u201376 United Counties League|1975\u201376]], earning promotion to Division One. After winning the Division One title in [[1981\u201382 United Counties League|1981\u201382]], they were promoted to the Premier Division. The club finished bottom of the Premier Division in [[1985\u201386 United Counties League|1985\u201386]] and was relegated back to Division One. They were Division One runners-up in [[1991\u201392 United Counties League|1991\u201392]], earning promotion back to the Premier Division, but were relegated to Division One after finishing bottom of the Premier Division in [[1996\u201397 United Counties League|1996\u201397]].<ref name=FCHD/>\n\nIn [[2001\u201302 United Counties League|2001\u201302]] Newport Pagnell were Division One champions and were promoted to the Premier Division, as well as winning the Berks & Bucks Intermediate Cup.<ref name=NLCD2017/> They were Premier Division runners-up the [[2002\u201303 United Counties League|following season]].<ref name=FCHD/> The club won the Berks & Bucks Senior Trophy in 2009\u201310 and retained it in 2010\u201311.<ref name=NLCD2017/> At the end of the [[2018\u201319 United Counties League|2018\u201319 season]] they were transferred to the Premier Division of the [[Spartan South Midlands Football League|Spartan South Midlands League]].\n\n==Ground==\nWillen Road, Newport Pagnell, Buckinghamshire. MK16 0DF\n\nThe club initially played on a pitch on Bury Field Common, using the Cannon pub on Union Street as changing rooms.<ref name=H/> When they moved up to the South Midlands League in 1971 the club played at the Youth Club in Wolverton Road, before relocating to the Willen Road Sports Ground in 1972.<ref name=H/> The new ground was opened with a match against [[Bletchley Town F.C.|Bletchley Town]].<ref name=H/> Willen Road currently has a capacity of 2,000, of which 100 is seated and covered.<ref name=NLCD2017/>\n\n==Honours==\n*'''United Counties League'''\n**Division One champions 1981\u201382, 2001\u201302\n*'''North Bucks & District League'''\n**Division One champions 1967\u201368, 1968\u201369, 1969\u201370\n**Division One Shield winners 1968-69\n**Division Two champions 1966\u201367\n**Division Two Shield winners 1966-67\n**Division Three champions 1965-66\n**Division Three Shield winners 1964\u201365\n*'''Berks & Bucks Senior Trophy'''\n**Winners 2009\u201310, 2010\u201311\n*'''Berks & Bucks Intermediate Cup'''\n**Winners 2001\u201302\n\n==Records==\n*Best [[FA Cup]] performance: Second qualifying round, 2008\u201309<ref name=FCHD/>\n*Best [[FA Vase]] performance: Quarter-finals, 2016\u201317<ref name=FCHD/>\n\n==See also==\n*[[:Category:Newport Pagnell Town F.C. players|Newport Pagnell Town F.C. players]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.pitchero.com/clubs/newportpagnelltown Official website]\n\n{{Spartan South Midlands League}}\n{{coord|52|04|36.80|N|0|43|15.93|W|region:GB_type:landmark|display=title}}\n\n[[Category:Football clubs in England]]\n[[Category:Football clubs in Buckinghamshire]]\n[[Category:Association football clubs established in 1963]]\n[[Category:1963 establishments in England]]\n[[Category:Sport in Milton Keynes]]\n[[Category:North Bucks & District Football League]]\n[[Category:South Midlands League]]\n[[Category:United Counties League]]\n[[Category:Spartan South Midlands Football League]]\n", "name_user": "SwansHistory", "label": "safe", "comment": "Updated History & Honours", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Newport_Pagnell_Town_F.C."}
{"title_page": "D. G. Scofield", "text_new": "{{short description|American businessman}}\n[[File:DemetriusGScofield.jpg|thumb|right|D. G. Scofield]]\n'''Demetrius G. Scofield''' (c. 1834 &ndash; July 31, 1917),<ref name=\"svchistory14\">[http://www.scvhistory.com/scvhistory/ripley14.htm Ripley: The San Fernando (Newhall) Pass, Part 14]</ref> more commonly '''D. G. Scofield''', was a pioneer of the oil business in [[California]] who founded a number of companies in that state and became the first president of [[Standard Oil of California]].<ref>[https://scvhistory.com/scvhistory/lw2223.htm  Ex-Pacific Coast Oil Co. Headquarters, Newhall, California]</ref><ref>[https://scvhistory.com/scvhistory/scofield.htm Ode to the Man Behind Mentryville\nBy DEMETRIUS G. SCOFIELD]</ref>\n\nHe served as secretary to the now-defunct [[F.W. Mitchell Oil Company]] of Pennsylvania during the [[Titusville, Pennsylvania|Titusville]] oil boom and arrived in California in about 1875,<ref name=\"svchistory14\"/> as the [[Pico Canyon Oilfield]] was being developed.  By 1876, he was the manager of the small refinery of the [[California Star Oil Works]], which was capable of refining up to {{convert|40|oilbbl|m3}} of oil a day.<ref name=\"svchistory14\"/> The facility, located at [[Lyons Station Stagecoach Stop|Lyon Station]] in [[Los Angeles County, California|Los Angeles County]] was the [[Pioneer Oil Refinery|first refinery in California]]. It is now abandoned but may be restored as an historical site.<ref>[http://www.placesearth.com/usa/california/los_angeles/pioneer_oil_refinory/pioneer_oil_ref0.shtml Places, Earth, Pioneer Oil Refinery]</ref> Scofield hired oil well driller [[Charles Alexander Mentry]] (1847-1900) and financing oil well of the Pico Canyon Oilfield.<ref>[https://www.elsmerecanyon.com/pioneerrefinery/history/history.htm The Pioneer Refinery in the early 1880's ]</ref><ref>[https://www.hmdb.org/Marker.asp?Marker=138355 Marker database First Commercial Oil Well In California, Pico #4]</ref>\n\nBy 1879 he was a key employee of the [[Pacific Coast Oil Company]]<ref>[http://www.scvhistory.com/scvhistory/ripley15.htm Ripley: The San Fernando (Newhall) Pass, Part 15]</ref> responsible for bringing other skilled workers to California. In that year, the Pacific Coast Oil Company completed a five-mile (8&nbsp;km) long, {{convert|2|in|mm|adj=mid|-diameter}} pipeline from Pico Canyon to a new refinery near [[Newhall, Santa Clarita, California|Newhall]].\n\nIn 1906, Pacific Coast Oil Company was acquired by [[Standard Oil]]. With the 1911 breakup of that corporation, Scofield became president of the new [[Standard Oil of California]].\n\nThe Associated Press reported that on July 30, he shot and killed himself at his home.  He was 74 and despondent over his wife's death five years before.<ref>Richmond Times-Dispatch. (Richmond, Va.), 31 July 1917. Page 1.</ref>\n\nHe was the namesake of the oil tanker, the MS D. G. Scofield which was, on 1 May 1939,<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.saudiembassy.net/files/PDF/Publications/Magazine/1996-Spring/aramco.html |title=Saudi Aramco: A Global Presence for Oil Market Stability |access-date=2010-02-04 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100428230932/http://www.saudiembassy.net/files/PDF/Publications/Magazine/1996-Spring/aramco.html |archive-date=2010-04-28 |url-status=dead }}</ref> the first oil tanker to load oil in [[Saudi Arabia]].\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Scofield, D. G.}}\n[[Category:Businesspeople from California]]\n[[Category:Standard Oil]]\n[[Category:1830s births]]\n[[Category:1917 deaths]]\n\n\n{{US-CEO-stub}}\n{{US-business-bio-1830s-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American businessman}}\n[[File:DemetriusGScofield.jpg|thumb|right|D. G. Scofield]]\n'''Demetrius G. Scofield''' (c. 1834 &ndash; July 31, 1917),<ref name=\"svchistory14\">[http://www.scvhistory.com/scvhistory/ripley14.htm Ripley: The San Fernando (Newhall) Pass, Part 14]</ref> more commonly '''D. G. Scofield''', was a pioneer of the oil business in [[California]] who founded a number of companies in that state and became the first president of [[Standard Oil of California]].<ref>[https://scvhistory.com/scvhistory/lw2223.htm  Ex-Pacific Coast Oil Co. Headquarters, Newhall, California]</ref><ref>[https://scvhistory.com/scvhistory/scofield.htm Ode to the Man Behind Mentryville\nBy DEMETRIUS G. SCOFIELD]</ref>\n\nHe served as secretary to the now-defunct [[F.W. Mitchell Oil Company]] of Pennsylvania during the [[Titusville, Pennsylvania|Titusville]] oil boom and arrived in California in about 1875,<ref name=\"svchistory14\"/> as the [[Pico Canyon Oilfield]] was being developed.  By 1876, he was the manager of the small refinery of the [[California Star Oil Works]], which was capable of refining up to {{convert|40|oilbbl|m3}} of oil a day.<ref name=\"svchistory14\"/> The facility, located at [[Lyons Station Stagecoach Stop|Lyon Station]] in [[Los Angeles County, California|Los Angeles County]] was the [[Pioneer Oil Refinery|first refinery in California]]. It is now abandoned but may be restored as an historical site.<ref>[http://www.placesearth.com/usa/california/los_angeles/pioneer_oil_refinory/pioneer_oil_ref0.shtml Places, Earth, Pioneer Oil Refinery]</ref> Scofield hired oil well driller [[Charles Alexander Mentry]] (1847-1900) and financing oil well of the Pico Canyon Oilfield.<ref>[https://www.elsmerecanyon.com/pioneerrefinery/history/history.htm The Pioneer Refinery in the early 1880's ]</ref><ref>[https://www.hmdb.org/Marker.asp?Marker=138355 Marker database First Commercial Oil Well In California, Pico #4]</ref>\n\nBy 1879 he was a key employee of the [[Pacific Coast Oil Company]]<ref>[http://www.scvhistory.com/scvhistory/ripley15.htm Ripley: The San Fernando (Newhall) Pass, Part 15]</ref> responsible for bringing other skilled workers to California. In that year, the Pacific Coast Oil Company completed a five-mile (8&nbsp;km) long, {{convert|2|in|mm|adj=mid|-diameter}} pipeline from Pico Canyon to a new refinery near [[Newhall, Santa Clarita, California|Newhall]].\n\nIn 1906, Pacific Coast Oil Company was acquired by [[Standard Oil]]. With the 1911 breakup of that corporation, Scofield became president of the new [[Standard Oil of California]].\n\nThe Associated Press reported that on July 30, he shot and killed himself at his home.  He was 74 and despondent over his wife's death five years before.<ref>Richmond Times-Dispatch. (Richmond, Va.), 31 July 1917. Page 1.</ref>\n\nHe was the namesake of the oil tanker, the MS D. G. Scofield which was, on 1 May 1939,<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.saudiembassy.net/files/PDF/Publications/Magazine/1996-Spring/aramco.html |title=Saudi Aramco: A Global Presence for Oil Market Stability |access-date=2010-02-04 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100428230932/http://www.saudiembassy.net/files/PDF/Publications/Magazine/1996-Spring/aramco.html |archive-date=2010-04-28 |url-status=dead }}</ref> the first oil tanker to load oil in [[Saudi Arabia]].\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Scofield, D. G.}}\n[[Category:Businesspeople from California]]\n[[Category:Standard Oil]]\n[[Category:1830s births]]\n[[Category:1917 deaths]]\n\n\n{{US-CEO-stub}}\n", "name_user": "GovernorLegislator", "label": "safe", "comment": "+{{US-business-bio-1830s-stub}} usingStubSorter", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/D._G._Scofield"}
{"title_page": "Yentl (film)", "text_new": "{{For|the original play|Yentl}}\n{{short description|1983 romantic musical drama film directed by Barbra Streisand}}\n{{Infobox film\n|name           = Yentl\n|image          = Yentl_poster.jpg\n|alt            =\n|caption        = Theatrical release poster\n|director       = [[Barbra Streisand]]\n|producer       = {{unbulleted list\n                  |Barbra Streisand\n                  |Larry DeWaay\n                  |[[Rusty Lemorande]]\n                  }}\n|screenplay     = Barbra Streisand <br> [[Jack Rosenthal]]\n|story          = [[Isaac Bashevis Singer]]\n|based on       = ''[[Yentl]]'' <br> by Leah Napolin <br> Isaac Bashevis Singer\n| starring = {{Plainlist|\n* Barbra Streisand\n* [[Mandy Patinkin]]\n* [[Amy Irving]]\n}}\n|music          = {{ubl\n                  |[[Michel Legrand]] {{small|(music)}}\n                  |[[Alan Bergman]] {{small|(lyrics)}}\n                  |[[Marilyn Bergman]] {{small|(lyrics)}}\n                  }}\n|cinematography = [[David Watkin (cinematographer)|David Watkin]]\n|editing        = [[Terry Rawlings]]\n|studio         = {{ubl\n                  |[[United Artists]]\n                  |[[Barwood Films]]\n                  |Ladbroke Entertainment\n                  }}\n|distributor    = [[Metro-Goldwyn-Mayer#MGM/UA Entertainment|MGM/UA Entertainment Company]]\n|released       = {{ubl\n                  |November 18, 1983 {{small|([[Limited release|Limited]])}}\n                  |January 6, 1984\n                  }}\n|runtime        = {{ubl\n                  |131 minutes\n                  |136 minutes {{small|(Extended cut)}}\n                  }}\n|country        = United States\n|language       = English\n|budget         = $16 million\n|gross          = $40.2 million<ref name=\"imdb.com\">{{cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0086619/business|title=Yentl|date=6 January 1984|publisher=|accessdate=30 October 2016|via=IMDb}}</ref>\n}}\n\n'''''Yentl''''' is a 1983 American [[romance film|romantic]] [[musical film|musical]] [[drama (film and television)|drama film]] directed, co-written, co-produced by, and starring [[Barbra Streisand]]. It is based on Leah Napolin and [[Isaac Bashevis Singer]]'s [[Yentl|play of the same name]], itself based on Singer's short story \"Yentl the Yeshiva Boy.\"\n\nThe dramatic story incorporates humor and music to relate the story of an [[Ashkenazi]] [[Judaism|Jewish]] girl in [[Poland]] who decides to dress and live like a man so that she can receive an education in [[Talmudic Law]] after her father dies. The film's [[Film score|musical score]] and songs, composed by [[Michel Legrand]], include the songs \"[[Papa, Can You Hear Me?]]\" and \"[[The Way He Makes Me Feel]]\", both sung by Streisand. The film received the [[Academy Award for Best Original Score]] and the [[Golden Globe Award]]s for [[Golden Globe Award for Best Motion Picture \u2013 Musical or Comedy|Best Motion Picture\u2014Musical or Comedy]] and [[Golden Globe Award for Best Director|Best Director]] for Streisand, making her the first, and only, woman to have won Best Director at the Golden Globes.\n\n==Plot==\n[[Barbra Streisand]] portrays Yentl Mendel, a girl living in an Ashkenazi [[shtetl]] named Pechev<ref>{{cite journal|last=Whitfield|first=Stephen|title=Yentl|journal=Jewish Social Studies|date=January 1999|page=154}}</ref> in [[Poland]] in 1904. Yentl's father, Rebbe Mendel ([[Nehemiah Persoff]]), secretly instructs her in the [[Talmud]] despite the proscription of such study by women according to the custom of her community.\n\nAfter the death of her father, Yentl decides to cut her hair short, dress like a man, take her late brother's name, Anshel, and enter a [[Yeshiva|Jewish religious school]] in [[Bychawa]]. Upon entering the yeshiva, Yentl befriends a fellow student, Avigdor ([[Mandy Patinkin]]), and meets his fianc\u00e9e, Hadass ([[Amy Irving]]). Things get complicated when Hadass's family cancels her wedding to Avigdor over fears that his family is tainted with insanity (his brother committed suicide), and decides that she should marry Anshel instead. Meanwhile, Hadass develops romantic feelings for Yentl (as Anshel), while Yentl herself is falling in love with Avigdor. After much turmoil, Avigdor and Hadass are reunited, while Yentl leaves [[Europe]] to go to the United States, where she hopes to lead a life with more freedom.\n\n==Themes==\n''Yentl'' begins with the same premise as Singer's original story. Streisand's character is a young woman growing up in an oppressive society that will not let her pursue her religious education. She is told she must have the \"soul of a man\" because of her desire to learn.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Whitfield|first=Stephen|title=Yentl|journal=Jewish Social Studies|date=Autumn 1998 \u2013 Winter 1999|volume=5|issue=1/2|page=154|doi=10.2979/jss.1998.5.1-2.154}}</ref> Her talent, curiosity and ambition are considered strictly masculine by her society and religious tradition. Unwilling to live without access to education on the basis of sex, Yentl leaves her home and conceals her sex to be able to pursue the scholarly occupation of a Jewish man. In doing so, Yentl inadvertently embarks on a journey of self-discovery that defies traditional ideas of gender roles within her community.\n\nYentl's defiance of social expectation and her reversal of traditional gender roles crosses deeply rooted religious boundaries, particularly once Yentl marries Hadass. Until this point, Yentl only adopts the appearance and occupation of a man, but now she lives as a man in a more complete sense, as a husband, occupying the traditionally male role in her household. Her identity as a woman, not only socially and religiously, but also personally and sexually, is called into question, as she occupies this role and develops an intimate, loving connection with Hadass, complete with hinted sexual chemistry.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Fernley|first=Allison|author2=Paula Maloof |title=Yentl by Barbra Streisand|journal=Film Quarterly|date=Spring 1985|volume=38|issue=3|page=43|doi=10.1525/fq.1985.38.3.04a00070}}</ref>\n\nIn Singer's story, this dual betrayal of nature and the divine plan dooms Yentl to a life of pain, alienation, and shameful dishonesty. After her marriage ends in disaster, Yentl remains trapped forever in her disguise, unable to find redemption from her rejection of a normal life\u2014a take on the legend of the [[Wandering Jew]].<ref>{{cite journal|last=Fernley|first=Allison|author2=Paula Maloof |title=Yentl by Barbra Streisand|journal=Film Quarterly|date=Spring 1985|volume=38|issue=3|pages=39\u201341|doi=10.1525/fq.1985.38.3.04a00070}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|last=Whitfield|first=Stephen|title=Yentl|journal=Jewish Social Studies|date=Autumn 1998 \u2013 Winter 1999|volume=5|issue=1/2|pages=170\u2013171|doi=10.2979/jss.1998.5.1-2.154}}</ref>\n\nIn Streisand's film, Yentl's defiance of expectation and definition, a rejection of sexist gender roles, is treated as a virtue. Though Yentl faces difficult choices in her attempt to live the life of her choosing, including sacrificing her love of Avigdor, she finds herself capable of following her dreams, of feeling different forms of love and intimacy with both sexes, as well as emerging from confusion and ambiguity with a powerful, independent sense of self-worth. At the film's conclusion, Yentl takes this developed, ever-evolving self to America to seek new possibilities and opportunities for discovery. Singer criticized the film's ending as hopelessly unrealistic, but the ending serves more as an affirmation of Yentl's independence and relentless optimism than a historically fitting conclusion to the narrative.<ref>[https://www.nytimes.com/books/97/04/27/reviews/streisand-singer.html \"I. B. Singer Talks to I. B. Singer About the Movie 'Yentl'\". ''New York Times''].</ref><ref>{{cite journal|last=Fernley|first=Allison|author2=Paula Maloof |title=Yentl by Barbra Streisand|journal=Film Quarterly|date=Spring 1985|volume=38|issue=3|pages=38\u201346|doi=10.1525/fq.1985.38.3.04a00070}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|last=Whitfield|first=Stephen|title=Yentl|journal=Jewish Social Studies|date=Autumn 1998 \u2013 Winter 1999|volume=5|issue=1/2|pages=160\u2013161|doi=10.2979/jss.1998.5.1-2.154}}</ref>\n\nThroughout her complex interaction with Hadass and Avigdor, Yentl manages conflict with empathy and\nrespect. Her difficult experiences expand, rather than trap her personality. She does not conform to expectations from her surroundings or from her audience, neither remaining merely a woman hiding in men's clothing nor revealing herself to be neutered or firmly homosexual. She refuses to accept a limited, traditional life, even when offered one in marriage to Avigdor. Rather, Yentl becomes a \"real woman,\" thoroughly modern and encompassing \"what society has defined as both masculine and\nfeminine traits.\"<ref name=\"Fernley 39\u201340\">{{cite journal|last=Fernley|first=Allison|author2=Paula Maloof |title=Yentl by Barbra Streisand|journal=Film Quarterly|date=Spring 1985|volume=38|issue=3|pages=39\u201340|doi=10.1525/fq.1985.38.3.04a00070}}</ref> In the end, her pain, her confusion and her loss never destroy her hope or resolve. She remains assertive and defiant, daring to find or to create room for new self-definition and new possibility, without seeking simple or complete resolution to ongoing challenges in her constant thirst for more.\n\nThough Isaac Bashevis Singer insisted that ''Yentl'' does not have feminist undertones,<ref>{{cite journal|last=Whitfield|first=Stephen|title=Yentl|journal=Jewish Social Studies|date=January 1999|volume=5|issue=1/2|pages=76\u2013154|doi=10.2979/jss.1998.5.1-2.154}}</ref> many critics and viewers of the film consider Yentl to be a feminist role model. One reason is that she rebels against patriarchal Orthodox Jewish society by disguising herself as a man to do what she loves\u2014study the Torah. Another reason is that although she finds herself in love with Avigdor, she has the strength to leave him behind, in exchange for a freer life in the US.<ref name=\"Fernley 39\u201340\"/>\n\n===Jewish-American themes===\nStreisand's interpretation of I. B. Singer's \"Yentl the Yeshiva Boy\" has philosophical implications as a Jewish-American film. Streisand changed Singer's specific ending, in which Yentl wanders off, presumably to a different yeshiva, to continue her studies and her cross-dressing. In the film interpretation of the story, Yentl moves on, but this time to the US. Viewers are led to believe that in the States she can have both study and womanhood. This idea symbolizes a refusal to conform to old-world Jewish standards and instead move \"against the authority and authenticity of the Judaic past,\" which Streisand asserts has \"propelled itself so far from the austerity of Talmudic study.\"<ref name=\"Whitfield 1999 154\">{{cite journal|last=Whitfield|first=Stephen|title=Yentl|journal=Jewish Social Studies|date=31 January 1999|page=154}}</ref>\n\nOften, Jewish-American immigrants who struck out on their own were unable to dedicate the amount of time and energy into text study that their ancestors had; their lives instead were characterized by an \"individualism and experimentalism\" that \"Jewish immigrants and their descendants have so strikingly honored, reinforced, and revised.\"<ref name=\"Whitfield 1999 154\"/> The differences between the written version of this story, which originated in Warsaw, and the American film interpretation thus symbolize a potential philosophical shift from the self-understanding of Eastern-European Jewry to Jewish-American self-understanding: it suggests America can potentially alter preexisting Jewish values.<ref name=\"Whitfield 1999 154\"/>\n\n===Heterosexual themes===\n''Yentl'' blurs lines between male and female and its characters develop attractions that could be seen as homosexual, although the film upholds a heterosexual sensibility. Yentl's desire is exclusively for her study partner, Avigdor, while her marriage to a woman remains unconsummated and comic throughout the film.  Because Yentl chooses to reveal herself as a woman to Avigdor in hopes of gaining his love, Yentl firmly establishes herself as a heterosexual female force in the film.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Rigney|first=Melissa|title=Brandon Goes to Hollywood: Boys Don't Cry and the Transgender Body in Film|journal=Film Criticism|date=Winter 2003}}</ref>\n\nWhile ''Yentl'' does not take its characters outside the realm of heterosexuality, the film critically questions the \"appropriateness of gender roles\" as determined by society.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Fernley|first=Allison|author2=Paula Maloof |title=Yentl|journal=Film Quarterly|date=1985|volume=38|issue=3|page=41}}</ref> Ultimately it argues that the society Yentl lived in does not allow equal opportunities for happiness for all people, especially women. In this way, it can be read as a heterosexual yet potentially feminist text.\n\n==Cast==\n* [[Barbra Streisand]] as Yentl Mendel\n* [[Mandy Patinkin]] as Avigdor\n* [[Amy Irving]] as Hadass Vishkower\n* [[Nehemiah Persoff]] as Rebbe Mendel\n* [[Steven Hill]] as Reb Alter Vishkower\n* [[Allan Corduner]] as Shimmele\n* [[Miriam Margolyes]] as Sarah\n* [[Doreen Mantle]] as Mrs Shaemen\n\n==Soundtrack==\n{{main|Yentl (soundtrack)}}\nThe [[soundtrack album]] to the film was released by [[Columbia Records]] in 1983.\n\n==Production==\nThe production of Barbra Streisand's film ''Yentl'' was a long and arduous process that delayed the project for over a decade.\n\nAfter reading Isaac Bashevis Singer's story \"Yentl: The Yeshiva Boy\" in 1968, Streisand sought to make it her next film after her completion of ''[[Funny Girl (film)|Funny Girl]]''.<ref name=\"Considine 1985 298\"/> The screen rights were gained in 1969, with Streisand to be the star.<ref>{{cite book|last=Spada|first=James|title=Streisand: Her Life|year=1995|publisher=Crown Publishers|location=201 East 50th St., New York, NY|page=402}}</ref> In 1971, the Czechoslovakian director, [[Ivan Passer]], was originally hired by First Artists to direct the film. Singer wrote the screenplay and retitled it \"Masquerade,\"<ref>{{cite book|last=Andersen|first=Christopher|title=Barbra: The Way She Is|year=2006|publisher=HarperCollins Publications|location=10 East 53rd st., New York, NY|page=275}}</ref> but because of his belief that Streisand's age and celebrity would detract from the film, Singer backed out.<ref name=\"Riese 1993 407\">{{cite book|last=Riese|first=Randall|title=Her Name Is Barbra|year=1993|publisher=Carol Publishing Group|location=600 Madison Ave. New York, NY|page=407}}</ref>\n\nIn 1973, Streisand read Singer's story to her then partner, producer [[Jon Peters]], to gain further support for the film. However, like Passer, he was convinced that Streisand was too old and feminine to convincingly play the part the film would demand.<ref name=\"Riese 1993 407\"/> By 1976, after completing  ''[[A Star Is Born (1976 film)|A Star Is Born]]'', Streisand became convinced that she was, in fact, too old to play the part in ''Yentl'', and would take up the film as director.<ref name=\"Considine 1985 298\">{{cite book|last=Considine|first=Shaun|title=Barbra Streisand: The Woman, The Myth, The Music|year=1985|publisher=Delacorte Press|location=1 Dag Hammarskjold Plaza, New York, NY|page=298}}</ref> Because she had wanted to be both the star and director, studios continued to draw back from funding the film, with the fear that Streisand as a rookie director would be unable to responsibly handle a multi-million dollar project.<ref>{{cite book|last=Riese|first=Randall|title=Barbra Streisand: The Woman, The Myth, The Music|year=1985|publisher=Delacorte Press|location=1 Dag Hammarskjold Plaza, New York, NY|page=298}}</ref> Additionally, Streisand reported that studios claimed the film was \"not commercial\" because it was \"too ethnic.\"<ref>{{cite news|last=Kroll|first=Jack|title=Barbra, the Yeshiva Boy|newspaper=Newsweek|date=1983|volume=102|issue=28|page=109}}</ref> In 1978, Streisand's friends, [[Alan and Marilyn Bergman]], suggested that ''Yentl'' be re-imagined as a musical. It was hoped that a musical starring Barbra Streisand would be accepted and better received by a studio.<ref name=\"Andersen 2006 277\">{{cite book|last=Andersen|first=Christopher|title=Barbra: The Way She Is|year=2006|publisher=HarperCollins Publications|location=10 East 53rd st., New York, NY|page=277}}</ref>\n\nJon Peters attempted to persuade Streisand to drop the project and perform at [[Wembley Stadium (1923)|Wembley Stadium]] in London instead, for an offer of $1 million. She refused the offer as well as the $2 million follow-up to reconsider.<ref>{{cite book|last=Riese|first=Randall|title=Her Name Is Barbra|year=1993|publisher=Carol Publishing|location=Madison Ave. New York, NY|page=411}}</ref> Another offer by Peters, which was to be in excess of $10 million for Streisand to perform in Las Vegas, was also promptly turned down in favor of pursuing the ''Yentl'' project.<ref>{{cite book|last=Andersen|first=Christopher|title=Barbra: The Way She Is|year=2006|publisher=HarperCollins Publications|location=10 East 53rd st., New York, NY|page=276}}</ref> Her attitude regarding her age quickly changed after she disguised herself as a man, temporarily confusing Peters into thinking that a stranger had broken into the house.<ref name=\"Andersen 2006 277\"/> Peters, now convinced of her ability to play a male, agreed to sign a three-year production contract with [[Orion Pictures]] in March 1978.<ref name=\"Riese 1993 408\">{{cite book|last=Riese|first=Randall|title=Her Name Is Barbra|year=1993|publisher=Carol Publishing|location=600 Madison Ave. New York, NY|page=408}}</ref> To combat the age she was to play in the film, she changed Yentl from being 16 to 26.<ref name=\"Andersen 2006 277\"/>\n\nAccording to various sources, Streisand became increasingly inspired and determined to bring ''Yentl'' into production when, in the summer of 1979, she and her brother Sheldon (Streisand) visited their father's grave at [[Mount Hebron Cemetery (New York City)|Mount Hebron Cemetery]] for the first time in 30 years. For the sake of making memory of the occasion, Streisand had her brother take a photo of her standing next to her father's tombstone. The photo revealed that Emmanual Streisand's grave was directly next to that of a man named Anshel, the name of Yentl's dead brother that Yentl adopts when she takes on a male identity. Intrigued, Streisand asked her brother to contact a psychic to perform a seance, convinced that her father was beckoning her from beyond the grave to complete the film.<ref>{{cite book|last=Andersen|first=Christopher|title=Barbra: The Way She Is|year=2006|publisher=HarperCollins Publications|location=10 East 53rd st., New York, NY|page=274}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last=Riese|first=Randall|title=Her Name Is Barbra|year=1993|publisher=Carol Publishing Group|location=600 Madison Ave. New York, NY|page=411}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last=Considine|first=Shaun|title=Barbra Streisand: The Woman, The Myth, The Music|year=1985|publisher=Delacorte Press|location=1 Dag Hammarskjold Plaza, New York, NY|page=300}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last=Spada|first=James|title=Streisand: Her Life|year=1995|publisher=Crown Publishers, Inc.|location=201 East 50th St., New York, NY|page=404}}</ref>\n\nIn 1979, Streisand finally reached an agreement with [[Orion Pictures]] to direct and star in ''Yentl''. She was working with a script by Ted Allen at the time, but discarded a majority of it, keeping the musical segments. The film was to be co-produced by Barbra's friends and associates: Joan Marshall Ashby and Jon Peters. To prepare for the film, Streisand exhaustively researched the many aspects of Judaism, ceremonies, relentless studying of the Torah, and consulted numerous rabbis,<ref name=\"Riese 1993 408\"/> one being Rabbi Lapin, whom Streisand appointed as the main religious consultant for the film.<ref>{{cite book|last=Riese|first=Randall|title=Her Name Is Barbra|year=1993|publisher=Carol Publishing|location=Madison Ave. New York, NY|page=410}}</ref>\n\nOrion Pictures made the announcement that it had agreed to produce ''Yentl'' as Barbra Streisand's directorial debut in the late summer of 1980. Traveling to Prague with a Super-8 camera and song lyrics, Streisand scouted out film locations while also shooting film of herself walking through the city in costume with early recordings of ''Yentl''{{'}}s soundtrack being played in the background.<ref>{{cite book|last=Andersen|first=Christopher|title=Barbra: The Way She Is|year=2006|publisher=HarperCollins|location=10 East 53rd st., New York, NY|page=278}}</ref> However, not long after her return, ''[[Heaven's Gate (film)|Heaven's Gate]]'' (1980), a [[Michael Cimino]] picture produced by United Artists, lost $35 million at the box office, bringing Orion to cancel all films that exceeded a $10 million production cost in order to preserve itself. ''Yentl'', which was priced at $14 million, was cancelled.<ref name=\"Considine 1985 298\"/> The film was turned down again and again until Jon Peters, Peter Gruber, and Neil Bogart formed PolyGram Pictures and agreed to produce the film. However, due to creative differences and personal disputes between Streisand and Peters, ''Yentl'' was dropped once again.<ref>{{cite book|last=Considine|first=Shaun|title=Barbra Streisand: The Woman, The Myth, The Music|year=1985|publisher=Delacorte Press|location=1 Dag Hammarskjold Plaza, New York , NY|page=299}}</ref>\n\nFifteen years after its original conception and 20 script variations later, ''Yentl''{{'}}s production finally began on April 14, 1982<ref>{{cite book|last=Andersen|first=Christopher|title=Barbra: The Way She Is|year=2006|publisher=HarperCollins|location=10 East 53rd st., New York, NY|page=281}}</ref> in the Lee International Studios of London,<ref>{{cite book|last=Considine|first=Shaun|title=Barbra Streisand: The Woman, The Myth, The Music|year=1985|publisher=Delacorte Press|location=1 Dag Hammarskjold Plaza, New York, NY|page=303}}</ref> after United Artists merged with MGM and gained the new leadership of Freddie Fields and [[David Begelman]]\u2014Streisand's former agent from the late sixties.<ref>{{cite book|last=Andersen|first=Christopher|title=Barbra: The Way She Is|year=2006|publisher=HarperCollins Publications|location=10 East 53rd st., New York, NY|page=279}}</ref> ''Yentl'' was green lighted as Streisand's directoral debut at a budget of $14.5 million.<ref>{{cite book|last=Considine|first=Shaun|title=Barbra Streisand: The Woman, The Myth, The Music|year=1985|publisher=Delacorte Press|location=1 Dag Hammarskjold Plaza, New York, NY|page=302}}</ref> Shooting concluded in October 1982, which was to be followed by Streisand requiring ten weeks to dub the soundtrack. In the end, the film went $1.5 million over budget, which Streisand paid for with her salary, as stated in the contract with UA.<ref>{{cite book|last=Andersen|first=Christopher|title=Barbra: The Way She Is|year=2006|publisher=HarperCollins|location=10 East 53rd st., New York, NY|page=283}}</ref>\n\n==Release==\n\n===Critical reception===\nThe film currently holds a 65% 'Fresh' rating at [[Rotten Tomatoes]] from 17 reviews.<ref>{{rotten-tomatoes|yentl|Yentl}}</ref>\nIt's featured on the [[National Board of Review: Top Ten Films|Top Ten Films of 1983]] by [[National Board of Review]].\n\n[[Roger Ebert]] gave the film 3{{frac|1|2}} out of 4 stars: \"''Yentl'' is a movie with a great middle ... the middle 100 minutes of the movie are charming and moving and surprisingly interesting.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rogerebert.com/reviews/yentl-1983|title=Yentl :: rogerebert.com :: Reviews |work=Chicago Sun Times |accessdate=May 27, 2012}}</ref>  In her review in ''[[The New Yorker]]'', [[Pauline Kael]] wrote: \"it has a distinctive and surprising spirit. It's funny, delicate, and intense\u2014all at the same time.\"<ref>{{cite web|title=Pauline Kael reviews 'Yentl'|url=http://www.geocities.ws/paulinekaelreviews/xy.html}}</ref> [[Jonathan Rosenbaum]], for the ''[[Chicago Reader]]'', praised Streisand's direction and Michel Legrand's music: \"The results may be a little protracted, but Streisand gives it her best shot, and the music by Michel Legrand is memorable.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.chicagoreader.com/chicago/yentl/Film?oid=106265 |title=Yentl Reviews |work=Chicago Sun Times |accessdate=May 27, 2012}}</ref> Isaac Bashevis Singer, writer of \"Yentl the Yeshiva Boy,\" the short story first published in English in 1983, said of Barbra Streisand's film adaptation: \"I did not find artistic merit neither in the adaptation, nor in the directing.\"<ref>{{cite news|last=Singer|first=Isaac Bashevis|title=.B. Singer Talks to I. B. Singer About the Movie 'Yentl'|url=https://www.nytimes.com/books/97/04/27/reviews/streisand-singer.html|publisher=The New York Times}}</ref>\n\nIn their 1985 ''[[Film Quarterly]]'' review, Allison Fernley and Paula Maloof lauded Streisand for departing from genre expectations, namely upholding Yentl as a strong female and therefore potential feminist role model rather than an accomplice in a male-dominated romance, for defying the expectations of the musical genre by choosing to give all musical parts to Yentl alone, and the \"subversion of the cross-dressing genre\" by refusing to end the film with a \"comfortable reassuring heterosexual union\" between Yentl and Avigdor, demanding the audience consider more serious questions about the role of societal conventions.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Fernley|first=Allison|author2=Paula Maloof |title=Yentl|journal=Film Quarterly|year=1985|volume=38|issue=3|page=41|doi=10.1525/fq.1985.38.3.04a00070}}</ref> Jack Kroll of ''Newsweek'' in 1983 called Streisand's control over the aesthetics of the film \"a delight and at times an astonishment.\"<ref>{{cite news|last=Kroll|first=Jack|title=Barbra, the Yeshiva Boy|newspaper=Newsweek|year=1983}}</ref> Gary Arnold of ''[[The Washington Post]]'' observed an \"uninspired score and other shortcomings\" of the film, but saw its \"exceptional charm and sentimental potency\" as its saving grace.<ref>{{cite news|last=Arnold|first=Gary|title=Barbra Streisand as Actor, Writer, Director: The Barriers Fall in an Endearing Triumph|newspaper=Washington Post|date=December 4, 1983}}</ref> While she granted Streisand a sincere effort in creating ''Yentl'', [[Janet Maslin]]'s ''[[The New York Times|New York Times]]'' review in 1983 criticized Streisand's carelessness with certain aesthetic elements of the film as well as the ending, which she described as a \"relatively harsh resolution,\" comparable to that of the original by I. B. Singer. Streisand responded publicly to Maslin, saying: \"I spent more than ten years researching the material; how long did she spend on it?\"<ref>{{cite news|last=Maslin|first=Janet|title=Yentl|newspaper=The New York Times}}</ref>\n\n===Box office===\n''Yentl'' was successful at the box office, opening at #5 at the US box office upon its [[limited release|limited-release]] weekend and stayed in the top 10 for 9 weeks, peaking at number three, in its third week. The film went on to gross more than $40,218,899 at the box office on a budget of $12 million, and was amongst the [[1983 in film|top 20 highest-grossing films of the year]] at the box office.<ref name=\"imdb.com\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=yentl.htm |title=Yentl (1983) |publisher=Box Office Mojo |accessdate=2012-03-16}}</ref> In rentals it also grossed $19,680,130. In [[Australia]], the film grossed $1.7 million and $2.3 million in Sweden.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0086619/business|title=Box office / business for Yentl (1983)|publisher=IMDB|accessdate=2012-03-16}}</ref>\n\n===Home media===\n''Yentl'' was released on home video in August 1984 on [[CBS/Fox Video]] (under license from [[MGM Home Entertainment|MGM/UA Home Entertainment Group, Inc.]]). Another VHS was released by MGM/UA Home Video in 1989. It was released on [[DVD]] by Metro-Goldwyn-Mayer (under [[20th Century Fox Home Entertainment]]) on February 3, 2009 as a two-disc \"[[Director's cut|Director's Extended Cut]]\" in the widescreen format. The DVD includes the theatrical cut, a director's extended cut with added scenes from Streisand's archives, an introduction by Streisand, an [[audio commentary]] with Streisand and [[Rusty Lemorande]], [[deleted scene]]s including a storyboard sequence for a cut song, pre-rehearsal concepts and feature comparisons, stills galleries, and cast and crew info. A [[Blu-ray]] edition is being released by Twilight Time.\n\n==Awards and honors==\n''Yentl'' won an [[Academy Awards|Academy Award]] in 1984 for [[Academy Award for Best Original Score|Best Adaptation Score]], the award going to [[Michel Legrand]] (music), [[Alan Bergman]] (lyrics), and [[Marilyn Bergman]] (lyrics). [[Amy Irving]] was nominated for the [[Academy Award for Best Supporting Actress]], and the film was also nominated for Best Art Direction/Set Decoration ([[Roy Walker (production designer)|Roy Walker]], [[Leslie Tomkins]], [[Tessa Davies]]).<ref name=\"NY Times\">{{cite web |url=https://movies.nytimes.com/movie/55765/Yentl/awards |title=NY Times: Yentl |accessdate=2009-01-01|work=NY Times}}</ref>\n\n[[Barbra Streisand]] became the first woman to receive a [[Golden Globe Award|Golden Globe]] for [[Golden Globe Award for Best Director|Best Director]] for the film, and ''Yentl'' was nominated for four other Golden Globes (Best Actress, Best Actor, Best Original Score and Best Original Song), also winning the award for [[Golden Globe Award for Best Motion Picture \u2013 Musical or Comedy|Best Motion Picture\u2014Musical or Comedy]].{{citation needed|date=January 2017}}\n\nThe film also nominated in [[Grammy Award for Best Score Soundtrack for Visual Media|Best Album of Instrumental Score Written for a Motion Picture or Television Special]] and Italian National Syndicate of Film Journalists' Special Silver Ribbon ('''''[[Nastro d'Argento]]''''') for the best new director of a foreign film and Best Foreign Actress.{{citation needed|date=January 2017}}\n\nThe film was chosen by ''[[Time (magazine)|Time]]'' magazine and [[National Board of Review]] as one of the top ten films of 1983. The DVD release won a Golden [[Satellite Awards]] for Best DVD Extras and was nominated for Best Classic DVD at the 2009 Satellite Awards.{{citation needed|date=January 2017}}\n\nIrving was also nominated for the [[Golden Raspberry Award]] for [[Golden Raspberry Award for Worst Supporting Actress|Worst Supporting Actress]], making her one of two actors to be nominated for an Oscar and a Razzie for the same performance; the other is [[James Coco]] for his performance in ''[[Only When I Laugh (film)|Only When I Laugh]]'').{{Citation needed|date=January 2011}} The film also earned Razzie nominations for Barbra Streisand as [[Golden Raspberry Award for Worst Actor|Worst Actor]], and for [[Golden Raspberry Award for Worst Musical Score|Worst Musical Score]].{{Citation needed|date=January 2011}}\n\nThe film is recognized by [[American Film Institute]] in these lists:\n* 2004: [[AFI's 100 Years...100 Songs]]:\n** \"[[Papa, Can You Hear Me?]]\" \u2013 Nominated<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.afi.com/Docs/100Years/songs400.pdf |title=AFI's 100 Years...100 Songs Nominees |format=PDF |date= |accessdate=2016-08-14}}</ref>\n* 2006: [[AFI's 100 Years...100 Cheers]] \u2013 Nominated<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.afi.com/Docs/100Years/cheers300.pdf |title=AFI's 100 Years...100 Cheers Nominees |format=PDF |date= |accessdate=2016-08-14}}</ref>\n* 2006: [[AFI's Greatest Movie Musicals]] \u2013 Nominated<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.afi.com/Docs/100Years/musicals_ballot.pdf |title= AFI's Greatest Movie Musicals Nominees |format=PDF |date= |accessdate=2016-08-14}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb title|0086619|Yentl}}\n* {{tcmdb title|17854|Yentl}}\n* {{mojo title|yentl|Yentl}}\n* {{rotten-tomatoes|yentl|Yentl}}\n\n{{Barbra Streisand}}\n{{Isaac Bashevis Singer}}\n{{Jack Rosenthal}}\n{{GoldenGlobeBestMotionPictureMusicalComedy 1981-2000}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Yentl (Film)}}\n[[Category:1983 films]]\n[[Category:1980s musical drama films]]\n[[Category:1980s LGBT-related films]]\n[[Category:1980s musical films]]\n[[Category:American musical drama films]]\n[[Category:American romantic musical films]]\n[[Category:American films]]\n[[Category:Best Musical or Comedy Picture Golden Globe winners]]\n[[Category:Films set in 1904]]\n[[Category:Films set in Poland]]\n[[Category:Films that won the Best Original Score Academy Award]]\n[[Category:Cross-dressing in American films]]\n[[Category:Cross-dressing in film]]\n[[Category:English-language films]]\n[[Category:1980s feminist films]]\n[[Category:Films scored by Michel Legrand]]\n[[Category:Films about Jews and Judaism]]\n[[Category:American films based on plays]]\n[[Category:Films based on works by Isaac Bashevis Singer]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Barbra Streisand]]\n[[Category:Same-sex marriage in film]]\n[[Category:Films with screenplays by Barbra Streisand]]\n[[Category:United Artists films]]\n[[Category:American historical romance films]]\n[[Category:LGBT-related musical films]]\n[[Category:Films shot in the Czech Republic]]\n[[Category:Barwood Films films]]\n[[Category:Metro-Goldwyn-Mayer films]]\n[[Category:Films produced by Barbra Streisand]]\n[[Category:Films based on adaptations]]\n[[Category:Films whose director won the Best Director Golden Globe]]\n[[Category:American historical musical films]]\n[[Category:1983 directorial debut films]]\n", "text_old": "{{For|the original play|Yentl}}\n{{short description|1983 romantic musical drama film directed by Barbra Streisand}}\n{{Infobox film\n|name           = Yentl\n|image          = Yentl_poster.jpg\n|alt            =\n|caption        = Theatrical release poster\n|director       = [[Barbra Streisand]]\n|producer       = {{unbulleted list\n                  |Barbra Streisand\n                  |Larry DeWaay\n                  |[[Rusty Lemorande]]\n                  }}\n|screenplay     = Barbra Streisand <br> [[Jack Rosenthal]]\n|story          = [[Isaac Bashevis Singer]]\n|based on       = ''[[Yentl]]'' <br> by Leah Napolin <br> Isaac Bashevis Singer\n| starring = {{Plainlist|\n* Barbra Streisand\n* [[Mandy Patinkin]]\n* [[Amy Irving]]\n}}\n|music          = {{ubl\n                  |[[Michel Legrand]] {{small|(music)}}\n                  |[[Alan Bergman]] {{small|(lyrics)}}\n                  |[[Marilyn Bergman]] {{small|(lyrics)}}\n                  }}\n|cinematography = [[David Watkin (cinematographer)|David Watkin]]\n|editing        = [[Terry Rawlings]]\n|studio         = {{ubl\n                  |[[United Artists]]\n                  |[[Barwood Films]]\n                  |Ladbroke Entertainment\n                  }}\n|distributor    = [[Metro-Goldwyn-Mayer#MGM/UA Entertainment|MGM/UA Entertainment Company]]\n|released       = {{ubl\n                  |November 18, 1983 {{small|([[Limited release|Limited]])}}\n                  |January 6, 1984\n                  }}\n|runtime        = {{ubl\n                  |131 minutes\n                  |136 minutes {{small|(Extended cut)}}\n                  }}\n|country        = United States\n|language       = English\n|budget         = $16 million\n|gross          = $40.2 million<ref name=\"imdb.com\">{{cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0086619/business|title=Yentl|date=6 January 1984|publisher=|accessdate=30 October 2016|via=IMDb}}</ref>\n}}\n\n'''''Yentl''''' is a 1983 American [[romance film|romantic]] [[musical film|musical]] [[drama (film and television)|drama film]] directed, co-written, co-produced by, and starring [[Barbra Streisand]]. It is based on Leah Napolin and [[Isaac Bashevis Singer]]'s [[Yentl|play of the same name]], itself based on Singer's short story \"Yentl the Yeshiva Boy.\"\n\nThe dramatic story incorporates humor and music to relate the story of an [[Ashkenazi]] [[Judaism|Jewish]] girl in [[Poland]] who decides to dress and live like a man so that she can receive an education in [[Talmudic Law]] after her father dies. The film's [[Film score|musical score]] and songs, composed by [[Michel Legrand]], include the songs \"[[Papa, Can You Hear Me?]]\" and \"[[The Way He Makes Me Feel]]\", both sung by Streisand. The film received the [[Academy Award for Best Original Score]] and the [[Golden Globe Award]]s for [[Golden Globe Award for Best Motion Picture \u2013 Musical or Comedy|Best Motion Picture\u2014Musical or Comedy]] and [[Golden Globe Award for Best Director|Best Director]] for Streisand, making her the first and only, woman to have won Best Director at the Golden Globes.\n\n==Plot==\n[[Barbra Streisand]] portrays Yentl Mendel, a girl living in an Ashkenazi [[shtetl]] named Pechev<ref>{{cite journal|last=Whitfield|first=Stephen|title=Yentl|journal=Jewish Social Studies|date=January 1999|page=154}}</ref> in [[Poland]] in 1904. Yentl's father, Rebbe Mendel ([[Nehemiah Persoff]]), secretly instructs her in the [[Talmud]] despite the proscription of such study by women according to the custom of her community.\n\nAfter the death of her father, Yentl decides to cut her hair short, dress like a man, take her late brother's name, Anshel, and enter a [[Yeshiva|Jewish religious school]] in [[Bychawa]]. Upon entering the yeshiva, Yentl befriends a fellow student, Avigdor ([[Mandy Patinkin]]), and meets his fianc\u00e9e, Hadass ([[Amy Irving]]). Things get complicated when Hadass's family cancels her wedding to Avigdor over fears that his family is tainted with insanity (his brother committed suicide), and decides that she should marry Anshel instead. Meanwhile, Hadass develops romantic feelings for Yentl (as Anshel), while Yentl herself is falling in love with Avigdor. After much turmoil, Avigdor and Hadass are reunited, while Yentl leaves [[Europe]] to go to the United States, where she hopes to lead a life with more freedom.\n\n==Themes==\n''Yentl'' begins with the same premise as Singer's original story. Streisand's character is a young woman growing up in an oppressive society that will not let her pursue her religious education. She is told she must have the \"soul of a man\" because of her desire to learn.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Whitfield|first=Stephen|title=Yentl|journal=Jewish Social Studies|date=Autumn 1998 \u2013 Winter 1999|volume=5|issue=1/2|page=154|doi=10.2979/jss.1998.5.1-2.154}}</ref> Her talent, curiosity and ambition are considered strictly masculine by her society and religious tradition. Unwilling to live without access to education on the basis of sex, Yentl leaves her home and conceals her sex to be able to pursue the scholarly occupation of a Jewish man. In doing so, Yentl inadvertently embarks on a journey of self-discovery that defies traditional ideas of gender roles within her community.\n\nYentl's defiance of social expectation and her reversal of traditional gender roles crosses deeply rooted religious boundaries, particularly once Yentl marries Hadass. Until this point, Yentl only adopts the appearance and occupation of a man, but now she lives as a man in a more complete sense, as a husband, occupying the traditionally male role in her household. Her identity as a woman, not only socially and religiously, but also personally and sexually, is called into question, as she occupies this role and develops an intimate, loving connection with Hadass, complete with hinted sexual chemistry.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Fernley|first=Allison|author2=Paula Maloof |title=Yentl by Barbra Streisand|journal=Film Quarterly|date=Spring 1985|volume=38|issue=3|page=43|doi=10.1525/fq.1985.38.3.04a00070}}</ref>\n\nIn Singer's story, this dual betrayal of nature and the divine plan dooms Yentl to a life of pain, alienation, and shameful dishonesty. After her marriage ends in disaster, Yentl remains trapped forever in her disguise, unable to find redemption from her rejection of a normal life\u2014a take on the legend of the [[Wandering Jew]].<ref>{{cite journal|last=Fernley|first=Allison|author2=Paula Maloof |title=Yentl by Barbra Streisand|journal=Film Quarterly|date=Spring 1985|volume=38|issue=3|pages=39\u201341|doi=10.1525/fq.1985.38.3.04a00070}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|last=Whitfield|first=Stephen|title=Yentl|journal=Jewish Social Studies|date=Autumn 1998 \u2013 Winter 1999|volume=5|issue=1/2|pages=170\u2013171|doi=10.2979/jss.1998.5.1-2.154}}</ref>\n\nIn Streisand's film, Yentl's defiance of expectation and definition, a rejection of sexist gender roles, is treated as a virtue. Though Yentl faces difficult choices in her attempt to live the life of her choosing, including sacrificing her love of Avigdor, she finds herself capable of following her dreams, of feeling different forms of love and intimacy with both sexes, as well as emerging from confusion and ambiguity with a powerful, independent sense of self-worth. At the film's conclusion, Yentl takes this developed, ever-evolving self to America to seek new possibilities and opportunities for discovery. Singer criticized the film's ending as hopelessly unrealistic, but the ending serves more as an affirmation of Yentl's independence and relentless optimism than a historically fitting conclusion to the narrative.<ref>[https://www.nytimes.com/books/97/04/27/reviews/streisand-singer.html \"I. B. Singer Talks to I. B. Singer About the Movie 'Yentl'\". ''New York Times''].</ref><ref>{{cite journal|last=Fernley|first=Allison|author2=Paula Maloof |title=Yentl by Barbra Streisand|journal=Film Quarterly|date=Spring 1985|volume=38|issue=3|pages=38\u201346|doi=10.1525/fq.1985.38.3.04a00070}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|last=Whitfield|first=Stephen|title=Yentl|journal=Jewish Social Studies|date=Autumn 1998 \u2013 Winter 1999|volume=5|issue=1/2|pages=160\u2013161|doi=10.2979/jss.1998.5.1-2.154}}</ref>\n\nThroughout her complex interaction with Hadass and Avigdor, Yentl manages conflict with empathy and\nrespect. Her difficult experiences expand, rather than trap her personality. She does not conform to expectations from her surroundings or from her audience, neither remaining merely a woman hiding in men's clothing nor revealing herself to be neutered or firmly homosexual. She refuses to accept a limited, traditional life, even when offered one in marriage to Avigdor. Rather, Yentl becomes a \"real woman,\" thoroughly modern and encompassing \"what society has defined as both masculine and\nfeminine traits.\"<ref name=\"Fernley 39\u201340\">{{cite journal|last=Fernley|first=Allison|author2=Paula Maloof |title=Yentl by Barbra Streisand|journal=Film Quarterly|date=Spring 1985|volume=38|issue=3|pages=39\u201340|doi=10.1525/fq.1985.38.3.04a00070}}</ref> In the end, her pain, her confusion and her loss never destroy her hope or resolve. She remains assertive and defiant, daring to find or to create room for new self-definition and new possibility, without seeking simple or complete resolution to ongoing challenges in her constant thirst for more.\n\nThough Isaac Bashevis Singer insisted that ''Yentl'' does not have feminist undertones,<ref>{{cite journal|last=Whitfield|first=Stephen|title=Yentl|journal=Jewish Social Studies|date=January 1999|volume=5|issue=1/2|pages=76\u2013154|doi=10.2979/jss.1998.5.1-2.154}}</ref> many critics and viewers of the film consider Yentl to be a feminist role model. One reason is that she rebels against patriarchal Orthodox Jewish society by disguising herself as a man to do what she loves\u2014study the Torah. Another reason is that although she finds herself in love with Avigdor, she has the strength to leave him behind, in exchange for a freer life in the US.<ref name=\"Fernley 39\u201340\"/>\n\n===Jewish-American themes===\nStreisand's interpretation of I. B. Singer's \"Yentl the Yeshiva Boy\" has philosophical implications as a Jewish-American film. Streisand changed Singer's specific ending, in which Yentl wanders off, presumably to a different yeshiva, to continue her studies and her cross-dressing. In the film interpretation of the story, Yentl moves on, but this time to the US. Viewers are led to believe that in the States she can have both study and womanhood. This idea symbolizes a refusal to conform to old-world Jewish standards and instead move \"against the authority and authenticity of the Judaic past,\" which Streisand asserts has \"propelled itself so far from the austerity of Talmudic study.\"<ref name=\"Whitfield 1999 154\">{{cite journal|last=Whitfield|first=Stephen|title=Yentl|journal=Jewish Social Studies|date=31 January 1999|page=154}}</ref>\n\nOften, Jewish-American immigrants who struck out on their own were unable to dedicate the amount of time and energy into text study that their ancestors had; their lives instead were characterized by an \"individualism and experimentalism\" that \"Jewish immigrants and their descendants have so strikingly honored, reinforced, and revised.\"<ref name=\"Whitfield 1999 154\"/> The differences between the written version of this story, which originated in Warsaw, and the American film interpretation thus symbolize a potential philosophical shift from the self-understanding of Eastern-European Jewry to Jewish-American self-understanding: it suggests America can potentially alter preexisting Jewish values.<ref name=\"Whitfield 1999 154\"/>\n\n===Heterosexual themes===\n''Yentl'' blurs lines between male and female and its characters develop attractions that could be seen as homosexual, although the film upholds a heterosexual sensibility. Yentl's desire is exclusively for her study partner, Avigdor, while her marriage to a woman remains unconsummated and comic throughout the film.  Because Yentl chooses to reveal herself as a woman to Avigdor in hopes of gaining his love, Yentl firmly establishes herself as a heterosexual female force in the film.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Rigney|first=Melissa|title=Brandon Goes to Hollywood: Boys Don't Cry and the Transgender Body in Film|journal=Film Criticism|date=Winter 2003}}</ref>\n\nWhile ''Yentl'' does not take its characters outside the realm of heterosexuality, the film critically questions the \"appropriateness of gender roles\" as determined by society.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Fernley|first=Allison|author2=Paula Maloof |title=Yentl|journal=Film Quarterly|date=1985|volume=38|issue=3|page=41}}</ref> Ultimately it argues that the society Yentl lived in does not allow equal opportunities for happiness for all people, especially women. In this way, it can be read as a heterosexual yet potentially feminist text.\n\n==Cast==\n* [[Barbra Streisand]] as Yentl Mendel\n* [[Mandy Patinkin]] as Avigdor\n* [[Amy Irving]] as Hadass Vishkower\n* [[Nehemiah Persoff]] as Rebbe Mendel\n* [[Steven Hill]] as Reb Alter Vishkower\n* [[Allan Corduner]] as Shimmele\n* [[Miriam Margolyes]] as Sarah\n* [[Doreen Mantle]] as Mrs Shaemen\n\n==Soundtrack==\n{{main|Yentl (soundtrack)}}\nThe [[soundtrack album]] to the film was released by [[Columbia Records]] in 1983.\n\n==Production==\nThe production of Barbra Streisand's film ''Yentl'' was a long and arduous process that delayed the project for over a decade.\n\nAfter reading Isaac Bashevis Singer's story \"Yentl: The Yeshiva Boy\" in 1968, Streisand sought to make it her next film after her completion of ''[[Funny Girl (film)|Funny Girl]]''.<ref name=\"Considine 1985 298\"/> The screen rights were gained in 1969, with Streisand to be the star.<ref>{{cite book|last=Spada|first=James|title=Streisand: Her Life|year=1995|publisher=Crown Publishers|location=201 East 50th St., New York, NY|page=402}}</ref> In 1971, the Czechoslovakian director, [[Ivan Passer]], was originally hired by First Artists to direct the film. Singer wrote the screenplay and retitled it \"Masquerade,\"<ref>{{cite book|last=Andersen|first=Christopher|title=Barbra: The Way She Is|year=2006|publisher=HarperCollins Publications|location=10 East 53rd st., New York, NY|page=275}}</ref> but because of his belief that Streisand's age and celebrity would detract from the film, Singer backed out.<ref name=\"Riese 1993 407\">{{cite book|last=Riese|first=Randall|title=Her Name Is Barbra|year=1993|publisher=Carol Publishing Group|location=600 Madison Ave. New York, NY|page=407}}</ref>\n\nIn 1973, Streisand read Singer's story to her then partner, producer [[Jon Peters]], to gain further support for the film. However, like Passer, he was convinced that Streisand was too old and feminine to convincingly play the part the film would demand.<ref name=\"Riese 1993 407\"/> By 1976, after completing  ''[[A Star Is Born (1976 film)|A Star Is Born]]'', Streisand became convinced that she was, in fact, too old to play the part in ''Yentl'', and would take up the film as director.<ref name=\"Considine 1985 298\">{{cite book|last=Considine|first=Shaun|title=Barbra Streisand: The Woman, The Myth, The Music|year=1985|publisher=Delacorte Press|location=1 Dag Hammarskjold Plaza, New York, NY|page=298}}</ref> Because she had wanted to be both the star and director, studios continued to draw back from funding the film, with the fear that Streisand as a rookie director would be unable to responsibly handle a multi-million dollar project.<ref>{{cite book|last=Riese|first=Randall|title=Barbra Streisand: The Woman, The Myth, The Music|year=1985|publisher=Delacorte Press|location=1 Dag Hammarskjold Plaza, New York, NY|page=298}}</ref> Additionally, Streisand reported that studios claimed the film was \"not commercial\" because it was \"too ethnic.\"<ref>{{cite news|last=Kroll|first=Jack|title=Barbra, the Yeshiva Boy|newspaper=Newsweek|date=1983|volume=102|issue=28|page=109}}</ref> In 1978, Streisand's friends, [[Alan and Marilyn Bergman]], suggested that ''Yentl'' be re-imagined as a musical. It was hoped that a musical starring Barbra Streisand would be accepted and better received by a studio.<ref name=\"Andersen 2006 277\">{{cite book|last=Andersen|first=Christopher|title=Barbra: The Way She Is|year=2006|publisher=HarperCollins Publications|location=10 East 53rd st., New York, NY|page=277}}</ref>\n\nJon Peters attempted to persuade Streisand to drop the project and perform at [[Wembley Stadium (1923)|Wembley Stadium]] in London instead, for an offer of $1 million. She refused the offer as well as the $2 million follow-up to reconsider.<ref>{{cite book|last=Riese|first=Randall|title=Her Name Is Barbra|year=1993|publisher=Carol Publishing|location=Madison Ave. New York, NY|page=411}}</ref> Another offer by Peters, which was to be in excess of $10 million for Streisand to perform in Las Vegas, was also promptly turned down in favor of pursuing the ''Yentl'' project.<ref>{{cite book|last=Andersen|first=Christopher|title=Barbra: The Way She Is|year=2006|publisher=HarperCollins Publications|location=10 East 53rd st., New York, NY|page=276}}</ref> Her attitude regarding her age quickly changed after she disguised herself as a man, temporarily confusing Peters into thinking that a stranger had broken into the house.<ref name=\"Andersen 2006 277\"/> Peters, now convinced of her ability to play a male, agreed to sign a three-year production contract with [[Orion Pictures]] in March 1978.<ref name=\"Riese 1993 408\">{{cite book|last=Riese|first=Randall|title=Her Name Is Barbra|year=1993|publisher=Carol Publishing|location=600 Madison Ave. New York, NY|page=408}}</ref> To combat the age she was to play in the film, she changed Yentl from being 16 to 26.<ref name=\"Andersen 2006 277\"/>\n\nAccording to various sources, Streisand became increasingly inspired and determined to bring ''Yentl'' into production when, in the summer of 1979, she and her brother Sheldon (Streisand) visited their father's grave at [[Mount Hebron Cemetery (New York City)|Mount Hebron Cemetery]] for the first time in 30 years. For the sake of making memory of the occasion, Streisand had her brother take a photo of her standing next to her father's tombstone. The photo revealed that Emmanual Streisand's grave was directly next to that of a man named Anshel, the name of Yentl's dead brother that Yentl adopts when she takes on a male identity. Intrigued, Streisand asked her brother to contact a psychic to perform a seance, convinced that her father was beckoning her from beyond the grave to complete the film.<ref>{{cite book|last=Andersen|first=Christopher|title=Barbra: The Way She Is|year=2006|publisher=HarperCollins Publications|location=10 East 53rd st., New York, NY|page=274}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last=Riese|first=Randall|title=Her Name Is Barbra|year=1993|publisher=Carol Publishing Group|location=600 Madison Ave. New York, NY|page=411}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last=Considine|first=Shaun|title=Barbra Streisand: The Woman, The Myth, The Music|year=1985|publisher=Delacorte Press|location=1 Dag Hammarskjold Plaza, New York, NY|page=300}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last=Spada|first=James|title=Streisand: Her Life|year=1995|publisher=Crown Publishers, Inc.|location=201 East 50th St., New York, NY|page=404}}</ref>\n\nIn 1979, Streisand finally reached an agreement with [[Orion Pictures]] to direct and star in ''Yentl''. She was working with a script by Ted Allen at the time, but discarded a majority of it, keeping the musical segments. The film was to be co-produced by Barbra's friends and associates: Joan Marshall Ashby and Jon Peters. To prepare for the film, Streisand exhaustively researched the many aspects of Judaism, ceremonies, relentless studying of the Torah, and consulted numerous rabbis,<ref name=\"Riese 1993 408\"/> one being Rabbi Lapin, whom Streisand appointed as the main religious consultant for the film.<ref>{{cite book|last=Riese|first=Randall|title=Her Name Is Barbra|year=1993|publisher=Carol Publishing|location=Madison Ave. New York, NY|page=410}}</ref>\n\nOrion Pictures made the announcement that it had agreed to produce ''Yentl'' as Barbra Streisand's directorial debut in the late summer of 1980. Traveling to Prague with a Super-8 camera and song lyrics, Streisand scouted out film locations while also shooting film of herself walking through the city in costume with early recordings of ''Yentl''{{'}}s soundtrack being played in the background.<ref>{{cite book|last=Andersen|first=Christopher|title=Barbra: The Way She Is|year=2006|publisher=HarperCollins|location=10 East 53rd st., New York, NY|page=278}}</ref> However, not long after her return, ''[[Heaven's Gate (film)|Heaven's Gate]]'' (1980), a [[Michael Cimino]] picture produced by United Artists, lost $35 million at the box office, bringing Orion to cancel all films that exceeded a $10 million production cost in order to preserve itself. ''Yentl'', which was priced at $14 million, was cancelled.<ref name=\"Considine 1985 298\"/> The film was turned down again and again until Jon Peters, Peter Gruber, and Neil Bogart formed PolyGram Pictures and agreed to produce the film. However, due to creative differences and personal disputes between Streisand and Peters, ''Yentl'' was dropped once again.<ref>{{cite book|last=Considine|first=Shaun|title=Barbra Streisand: The Woman, The Myth, The Music|year=1985|publisher=Delacorte Press|location=1 Dag Hammarskjold Plaza, New York , NY|page=299}}</ref>\n\nFifteen years after its original conception and 20 script variations later, ''Yentl''{{'}}s production finally began on April 14, 1982<ref>{{cite book|last=Andersen|first=Christopher|title=Barbra: The Way She Is|year=2006|publisher=HarperCollins|location=10 East 53rd st., New York, NY|page=281}}</ref> in the Lee International Studios of London,<ref>{{cite book|last=Considine|first=Shaun|title=Barbra Streisand: The Woman, The Myth, The Music|year=1985|publisher=Delacorte Press|location=1 Dag Hammarskjold Plaza, New York, NY|page=303}}</ref> after United Artists merged with MGM and gained the new leadership of Freddie Fields and [[David Begelman]]\u2014Streisand's former agent from the late sixties.<ref>{{cite book|last=Andersen|first=Christopher|title=Barbra: The Way She Is|year=2006|publisher=HarperCollins Publications|location=10 East 53rd st., New York, NY|page=279}}</ref> ''Yentl'' was green lighted as Streisand's directoral debut at a budget of $14.5 million.<ref>{{cite book|last=Considine|first=Shaun|title=Barbra Streisand: The Woman, The Myth, The Music|year=1985|publisher=Delacorte Press|location=1 Dag Hammarskjold Plaza, New York, NY|page=302}}</ref> Shooting concluded in October 1982, which was to be followed by Streisand requiring ten weeks to dub the soundtrack. In the end, the film went $1.5 million over budget, which Streisand paid for with her salary, as stated in the contract with UA.<ref>{{cite book|last=Andersen|first=Christopher|title=Barbra: The Way She Is|year=2006|publisher=HarperCollins|location=10 East 53rd st., New York, NY|page=283}}</ref>\n\n==Release==\n\n===Critical reception===\nThe film currently holds a 65% 'Fresh' rating at [[Rotten Tomatoes]] from 17 reviews.<ref>{{rotten-tomatoes|yentl|Yentl}}</ref>\nIt's featured on the [[National Board of Review: Top Ten Films|Top Ten Films of 1983]] by [[National Board of Review]].\n\n[[Roger Ebert]] gave the film 3{{frac|1|2}} out of 4 stars: \"''Yentl'' is a movie with a great middle ... the middle 100 minutes of the movie are charming and moving and surprisingly interesting.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rogerebert.com/reviews/yentl-1983|title=Yentl :: rogerebert.com :: Reviews |work=Chicago Sun Times |accessdate=May 27, 2012}}</ref>  In her review in ''[[The New Yorker]]'', [[Pauline Kael]] wrote: \"it has a distinctive and surprising spirit. It's funny, delicate, and intense\u2014all at the same time.\"<ref>{{cite web|title=Pauline Kael reviews 'Yentl'|url=http://www.geocities.ws/paulinekaelreviews/xy.html}}</ref> [[Jonathan Rosenbaum]], for the ''[[Chicago Reader]]'', praised Streisand's direction and Michel Legrand's music: \"The results may be a little protracted, but Streisand gives it her best shot, and the music by Michel Legrand is memorable.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.chicagoreader.com/chicago/yentl/Film?oid=106265 |title=Yentl Reviews |work=Chicago Sun Times |accessdate=May 27, 2012}}</ref> Isaac Bashevis Singer, writer of \"Yentl the Yeshiva Boy,\" the short story first published in English in 1983, said of Barbra Streisand's film adaptation: \"I did not find artistic merit neither in the adaptation, nor in the directing.\"<ref>{{cite news|last=Singer|first=Isaac Bashevis|title=.B. Singer Talks to I. B. Singer About the Movie 'Yentl'|url=https://www.nytimes.com/books/97/04/27/reviews/streisand-singer.html|publisher=The New York Times}}</ref>\n\nIn their 1985 ''[[Film Quarterly]]'' review, Allison Fernley and Paula Maloof lauded Streisand for departing from genre expectations, namely upholding Yentl as a strong female and therefore potential feminist role model rather than an accomplice in a male-dominated romance, for defying the expectations of the musical genre by choosing to give all musical parts to Yentl alone, and the \"subversion of the cross-dressing genre\" by refusing to end the film with a \"comfortable reassuring heterosexual union\" between Yentl and Avigdor, demanding the audience consider more serious questions about the role of societal conventions.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Fernley|first=Allison|author2=Paula Maloof |title=Yentl|journal=Film Quarterly|year=1985|volume=38|issue=3|page=41|doi=10.1525/fq.1985.38.3.04a00070}}</ref> Jack Kroll of ''Newsweek'' in 1983 called Streisand's control over the aesthetics of the film \"a delight and at times an astonishment.\"<ref>{{cite news|last=Kroll|first=Jack|title=Barbra, the Yeshiva Boy|newspaper=Newsweek|year=1983}}</ref> Gary Arnold of ''[[The Washington Post]]'' observed an \"uninspired score and other shortcomings\" of the film, but saw its \"exceptional charm and sentimental potency\" as its saving grace.<ref>{{cite news|last=Arnold|first=Gary|title=Barbra Streisand as Actor, Writer, Director: The Barriers Fall in an Endearing Triumph|newspaper=Washington Post|date=December 4, 1983}}</ref> While she granted Streisand a sincere effort in creating ''Yentl'', [[Janet Maslin]]'s ''[[The New York Times|New York Times]]'' review in 1983 criticized Streisand's carelessness with certain aesthetic elements of the film as well as the ending, which she described as a \"relatively harsh resolution,\" comparable to that of the original by I. B. Singer. Streisand responded publicly to Maslin, saying: \"I spent more than ten years researching the material; how long did she spend on it?\"<ref>{{cite news|last=Maslin|first=Janet|title=Yentl|newspaper=The New York Times}}</ref>\n\n===Box office===\n''Yentl'' was successful at the box office, opening at #5 at the US box office upon its [[limited release|limited-release]] weekend and stayed in the top 10 for 9 weeks, peaking at number three, in its third week. The film went on to gross more than $40,218,899 at the box office on a budget of $12 million, and was amongst the [[1983 in film|top 20 highest-grossing films of the year]] at the box office.<ref name=\"imdb.com\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=yentl.htm |title=Yentl (1983) |publisher=Box Office Mojo |accessdate=2012-03-16}}</ref> In rentals it also grossed $19,680,130. In [[Australia]], the film grossed $1.7 million and $2.3 million in Sweden.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0086619/business|title=Box office / business for Yentl (1983)|publisher=IMDB|accessdate=2012-03-16}}</ref>\n\n===Home media===\n''Yentl'' was released on home video in August 1984 on [[CBS/Fox Video]] (under license from [[MGM Home Entertainment|MGM/UA Home Entertainment Group, Inc.]]). Another VHS was released by MGM/UA Home Video in 1989. It was released on [[DVD]] by Metro-Goldwyn-Mayer (under [[20th Century Fox Home Entertainment]]) on February 3, 2009 as a two-disc \"[[Director's cut|Director's Extended Cut]]\" in the widescreen format. The DVD includes the theatrical cut, a director's extended cut with added scenes from Streisand's archives, an introduction by Streisand, an [[audio commentary]] with Streisand and [[Rusty Lemorande]], [[deleted scene]]s including a storyboard sequence for a cut song, pre-rehearsal concepts and feature comparisons, stills galleries, and cast and crew info. A [[Blu-ray]] edition is being released by Twilight Time.\n\n==Awards and honors==\n''Yentl'' won an [[Academy Awards|Academy Award]] in 1984 for [[Academy Award for Best Original Score|Best Adaptation Score]], the award going to [[Michel Legrand]] (music), [[Alan Bergman]] (lyrics), and [[Marilyn Bergman]] (lyrics). [[Amy Irving]] was nominated for the [[Academy Award for Best Supporting Actress]], and the film was also nominated for Best Art Direction/Set Decoration ([[Roy Walker (production designer)|Roy Walker]], [[Leslie Tomkins]], [[Tessa Davies]]).<ref name=\"NY Times\">{{cite web |url=https://movies.nytimes.com/movie/55765/Yentl/awards |title=NY Times: Yentl |accessdate=2009-01-01|work=NY Times}}</ref>\n\n[[Barbra Streisand]] became the first woman to receive a [[Golden Globe Award|Golden Globe]] for [[Golden Globe Award for Best Director|Best Director]] for the film, and ''Yentl'' was nominated for four other Golden Globes (Best Actress, Best Actor, Best Original Score and Best Original Song), also winning the award for [[Golden Globe Award for Best Motion Picture \u2013 Musical or Comedy|Best Motion Picture\u2014Musical or Comedy]].{{citation needed|date=January 2017}}\n\nThe film also nominated in [[Grammy Award for Best Score Soundtrack for Visual Media|Best Album of Instrumental Score Written for a Motion Picture or Television Special]] and Italian National Syndicate of Film Journalists' Special Silver Ribbon ('''''[[Nastro d'Argento]]''''') for the best new director of a foreign film and Best Foreign Actress.{{citation needed|date=January 2017}}\n\nThe film was chosen by ''[[Time (magazine)|Time]]'' magazine and [[National Board of Review]] as one of the top ten films of 1983. The DVD release won a Golden [[Satellite Awards]] for Best DVD Extras and was nominated for Best Classic DVD at the 2009 Satellite Awards.{{citation needed|date=January 2017}}\n\nIrving was also nominated for the [[Golden Raspberry Award]] for [[Golden Raspberry Award for Worst Supporting Actress|Worst Supporting Actress]], making her one of two actors to be nominated for an Oscar and a Razzie for the same performance; the other is [[James Coco]] for his performance in ''[[Only When I Laugh (film)|Only When I Laugh]]'').{{Citation needed|date=January 2011}} The film also earned Razzie nominations for Barbra Streisand as [[Golden Raspberry Award for Worst Actor|Worst Actor]], and for [[Golden Raspberry Award for Worst Musical Score|Worst Musical Score]].{{Citation needed|date=January 2011}}\n\nThe film is recognized by [[American Film Institute]] in these lists:\n* 2004: [[AFI's 100 Years...100 Songs]]:\n** \"[[Papa, Can You Hear Me?]]\" \u2013 Nominated<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.afi.com/Docs/100Years/songs400.pdf |title=AFI's 100 Years...100 Songs Nominees |format=PDF |date= |accessdate=2016-08-14}}</ref>\n* 2006: [[AFI's 100 Years...100 Cheers]] \u2013 Nominated<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.afi.com/Docs/100Years/cheers300.pdf |title=AFI's 100 Years...100 Cheers Nominees |format=PDF |date= |accessdate=2016-08-14}}</ref>\n* 2006: [[AFI's Greatest Movie Musicals]] \u2013 Nominated<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.afi.com/Docs/100Years/musicals_ballot.pdf |title= AFI's Greatest Movie Musicals Nominees |format=PDF |date= |accessdate=2016-08-14}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb title|0086619|Yentl}}\n* {{tcmdb title|17854|Yentl}}\n* {{mojo title|yentl|Yentl}}\n* {{rotten-tomatoes|yentl|Yentl}}\n\n{{Barbra Streisand}}\n{{Isaac Bashevis Singer}}\n{{Jack Rosenthal}}\n{{GoldenGlobeBestMotionPictureMusicalComedy 1981-2000}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Yentl (Film)}}\n[[Category:1983 films]]\n[[Category:1980s musical drama films]]\n[[Category:1980s LGBT-related films]]\n[[Category:1980s musical films]]\n[[Category:American musical drama films]]\n[[Category:American romantic musical films]]\n[[Category:American films]]\n[[Category:Best Musical or Comedy Picture Golden Globe winners]]\n[[Category:Films set in 1904]]\n[[Category:Films set in Poland]]\n[[Category:Films that won the Best Original Score Academy Award]]\n[[Category:Cross-dressing in American films]]\n[[Category:Cross-dressing in film]]\n[[Category:English-language films]]\n[[Category:1980s feminist films]]\n[[Category:Films scored by Michel Legrand]]\n[[Category:Films about Jews and Judaism]]\n[[Category:American films based on plays]]\n[[Category:Films based on works by Isaac Bashevis Singer]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Barbra Streisand]]\n[[Category:Same-sex marriage in film]]\n[[Category:Films with screenplays by Barbra Streisand]]\n[[Category:United Artists films]]\n[[Category:American historical romance films]]\n[[Category:LGBT-related musical films]]\n[[Category:Films shot in the Czech Republic]]\n[[Category:Barwood Films films]]\n[[Category:Metro-Goldwyn-Mayer films]]\n[[Category:Films produced by Barbra Streisand]]\n[[Category:Films based on adaptations]]\n[[Category:Films whose director won the Best Director Golden Globe]]\n[[Category:American historical musical films]]\n[[Category:1983 directorial debut films]]\n", "name_user": "Thisisananonymous", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Yentl_(film)"}
{"title_page": "Solenopsis abdita", "text_new": "{{short description|Species of ant}}\n{{Speciesbox\n| image = Solenopsis abdita casent0104494 profile 1.jpg\n| genus = Solenopsis\n| species = abdita\n| authority = Thompson, 1989\n}}\n'''''Solenopsis abdita''''' is a species of '''thief ant''' in the ''[[Solenopsis molesta]]'' complex, first described in 1989 in Florida. It is native to [[Florida]] but may be found in the surrounding states, though this is not confirmed. This species can be hard to differentiate from ''[[Solenopsis texana]]'' and [[Solenopsis carolinensis|''S. carolinensis'']], but there are a few minor differences, such as having a longer [[Antenna (biology)#Structure|scape]] and a wider [[Petiole (insect anatomy)|petiole]]. Thus, the main method used to distinguish these species primarily uses [[Gyne|queens]] and males, though unfortunately usually only workers are collected, making it difficult to correctly identify this species. ''S. molesta'' is known to nest in rotten wood in [[pine]]\u2013[[oak]] forests, and workers have been collected from [[leaf litter]] in said forests.<ref name=\":0\">{{cite journal|last=Thompson|first=C. R.|year=1989|title=The thief ants, ''Solenopsis molesta'' group, of Florida (Hymenoptera: Formicidae)|journal=Florida Entomologist|pages=268-283|url=http://antbase.org/ants/publications/2870/2870.pdf}}</ref><ref name=\":1\">{{Cite book|url=http://www.antwiki.org/wiki/images/4/4b/Pacheco%2C_J.A._%26_Mackay%2C_W.P._2013._The_systematics_and_biology_of_the_New_World_thief_ants_of_the_genus_Solenopsis.pdf|title=The Systematics and Biology of The New World Thief Ants of the Genus Solenopsis (Hymenoptera: Formicidae)|last=Mackay|first=William P.|last2=Pacheco|first2=Jocely|publisher=|year=2013|isbn=0773443428|location=|pages=102-105}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.antwiki.org/wiki/Solenopsis_molesta_species_complex|title=Solenopsis molesta species complex - AntWiki|website=www.antwiki.org|access-date=2019-06-09}}</ref><ref name=\":2\">{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=5SuLDQAAQBAJ&pg=PP197&lpg=PP197&dq=Solenopsis+abdita&source=bl&ots=Jjd3IqbC90&sig=ACfU3U14aaFzyuGe_V--iFPd2Vls5_YiVQ&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjd3aOZkOPiAhUPUK0KHUC6C2w4ChDoATAAegQICBAB#v=onepage&q=Solenopsis%20abdita&f=false|title=Ants of Florida: Identification and Natural History|last=Deyrup|first=Mark|publisher=|year=2017|isbn=1498754678|location=|pages=}}</ref>\n\n== Etymology ==\nThe species' name ''abdita'' is a [[Latin]] word meaning \"concealed\". This is a reference to this species' visual similarity with [[Solenopsis carolinensis|''S. carolinensis'']] and [[Solenopsis texana|''S. texana'']] and others in the ''molesta'' complex which makes this species hard to identify and had helped to delay the process of describing the species.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":1\" /><ref name=\":2\" />\n\n== Appearance ==\nWorkers in this species are colored yellow and measure 1.1-1.3mm(0.04-0.05 inches) in length, and are almost identical in appearance to [[Solenopsis carolinensis|''carolinensis'']] and ''[[Solenopsis texana|texana]]'', as well as other [[Florida|Floridian]] species of the ''molesta'' complex. [[Gyne|Queens]] appear brown to dark brown, possessing white wings; these [[Gyne|reproductive females]], along with males, are the main evidence used towards identifying this species, as they are easily distinguishable from [[Gyne|reproductive ants]] of other species. <ref name=\":2\" /> \n\n<br />\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}{{Taxonbar|from=Q3721593}}\n[[Category:Solenopsis|abdita]]\n[[Category:Insects described in 1989]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Species of ant}}\n{{Speciesbox\n| image = Solenopsis abdita casent0104494 profile 1.jpg\n| genus = Solenopsis\n| species = abdita\n| authority = Thompson, 1989\n}}\n'''''Solenopsis abdita''''' is a species of '''thief ant''' in the ''[[Solenopsis molesta]]'' complex. It was first described in 1989 in Florida. It is native to [[Florida]] but may be found in the surrounding states, though this is not confirmed. This species can be hard to differentiate from ''[[Solenopsis texana]]'' and [[Solenopsis carolinensis|''S. carolinensis'']], but there are a few minor differences, such as having a longer [[Antenna (biology)#Structure|scape]] and a wider [[Petiole (insect anatomy)|petiole]]. Thus, the main method used to distinguish these species primarily uses [[Gyne|queens]] and males, though unfortunately usually only workers are collected, making it difficult to correctly identify this species. ''S. molesta'' is known to nest in rotten wood in [[pine]]\u2013[[oak]] forests, and workers have been collected from [[leaf litter]] in said forests.<ref name=\":0\">{{cite journal|last=Thompson|first=C. R.|year=1989|title=The thief ants, ''Solenopsis molesta'' group, of Florida (Hymenoptera: Formicidae)|journal=Florida Entomologist|pages=268-283|url=http://antbase.org/ants/publications/2870/2870.pdf}}</ref><ref name=\":1\">{{Cite book|url=http://www.antwiki.org/wiki/images/4/4b/Pacheco%2C_J.A._%26_Mackay%2C_W.P._2013._The_systematics_and_biology_of_the_New_World_thief_ants_of_the_genus_Solenopsis.pdf|title=The Systematics and Biology of The New World Thief Ants of the Genus Solenopsis (Hymenoptera: Formicidae)|last=Mackay|first=William P.|last2=Pacheco|first2=Jocely|publisher=|year=2013|isbn=0773443428|location=|pages=102-105}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.antwiki.org/wiki/Solenopsis_molesta_species_complex|title=Solenopsis molesta species complex - AntWiki|website=www.antwiki.org|access-date=2019-06-09}}</ref><ref name=\":2\">{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=5SuLDQAAQBAJ&pg=PP197&lpg=PP197&dq=Solenopsis+abdita&source=bl&ots=Jjd3IqbC90&sig=ACfU3U14aaFzyuGe_V--iFPd2Vls5_YiVQ&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjd3aOZkOPiAhUPUK0KHUC6C2w4ChDoATAAegQICBAB#v=onepage&q=Solenopsis%20abdita&f=false|title=Ants of Florida: Identification and Natural History|last=Deyrup|first=Mark|publisher=|year=2017|isbn=1498754678|location=|pages=}}</ref>\n\n== Etymology ==\nThe species' name ''abdita'' is a [[Latin]] word meaning \"concealed\". This is a reference to this species' visual similarity with [[Solenopsis carolinensis|''S. carolinensis'']] and [[Solenopsis texana|''S. texana'']] and others in the ''molesta'' complex which makes this species hard to identify and had helped to delay the process of describing the species.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":1\" /><ref name=\":2\" />\n\n== Appearance ==\nWorkers in this species are colored yellow and measure 1.1-1.3mm(0.04-0.05 inches) in length, and are almost identical in appearance to [[Solenopsis carolinensis|''carolinensis'']] and ''[[Solenopsis texana|texana]]'', as well as other [[Florida|Floridian]] species of the ''molesta'' complex. [[Gyne|Queens]] appear brown to dark brown, possessing white wings; these [[Gyne|reproductive females]], along with males, are the main evidence used towards identifying this species, as they are easily distinguishable from [[Gyne|reproductive ants]] of other species. <ref name=\":2\" /> \n\n<br />\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}{{Taxonbar|from=Q3721593}}\n[[Category:Solenopsis|abdita]]\n[[Category:Insects described in 1989]]\n", "name_user": "BugBaron", "label": "safe", "comment": "combined sentences", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Solenopsis_abdita"}
